column12: Improvements in Clips and Clip Releasers for Cable Haulage
column13: 17,757. Berry, J., and Berry, F. Aug. 17. Rope grips.-Consists of a clip or grip for cable haulage in collieries &c., and of means for automatically releasing the same. Figs. 1 and 4 show the clip, and Fig. 5 the releaser. Pivoted in a body piece a are jaws e, e<1> the lower ends of which embrace the cable. A top jaw h slides in slots in the piece a. The jaws e, e<1> are weighted so that when free of the cable they open, but when the clip is placed on the rope the jaw h separates the top parts of the jaws e, e<1> enough to allow the thin part of the wedge-shaped cam-lever c, d to enter between them. On then depressing this lever, the edge of the cam engages the inclined top of the jaw h, and its sides the jaws e, e', and all three jaws are thus closed on the cable. The releaser comprises a trough k with a supporting-roller l for the cable, and a pivoted cross-arm n on to which the cam lever c, d passes to be lifted. An incline o on the clip raises the arm n to allow of the passage of the clip, after which the arm drops again to its operative position.

column12: Improvements in loading machines
column13: 731,546. Jigging conveyers. DISTINGTON ENGINEERING CO., Ltd. Sept. 7, 1953 [Sept. 11, 1952], No. 22830/52. Class 78 (1). A machine for loading coal or other loose material comprises in combination a shaker conveyer 1, Figs. 1 and 2, which includes a shovel 4 and drive mechanism 2 therefor and for steerable propelling means 3, the conveyer being arranged wholly in front of the drive mechanism and being adapted to discharge material through a curved trough 5 at a height less than that of the drive mechanism. The shovel and trough are mounted on a vertical pivot pin 6, Fig. 7, carried by a frarne 7 which is slidable longitudinally of the machine on ball bearings 8 carried by a skid. plate 9. A pin 12, Fig. 9, fixed to the shovel 4, is rotatably mounted in a carriage 13 which travels in guides 14. These guides are secured to a shoe 15, Fig. 8, which is slidable in lateral guides 16 mounted on the skid. The shoe 15 is connected by a link 18, Fig. 3, and a bell-crank lever 19 to the piston rod of a double-acting hydraulic cylinder 17. The frame 7 is pivotally connected to one end of a rod 11, the other end of which is pivotally connected to a lever 32. This lever is connected by a rocker arm 31, coupling rod 30, bell-crank lever 29 and connecting rod 28 to a crank-shaft 27, Fig. 5. The crank-shaft is driven through spur gearing by a shaft 24 which is driven by an electric motor 23. The shaft 24 drives a hydraulic pump 25 which supplies fluid to the cylinder 17 and to two variable speed motors 26 which drive the endless tracks 3. The upper end of the lever 32 is connected by a link 35 to a shaft 36, the ends of which engage balance weights 33 slidably mounted on guides 34.

Improvements in Apparatus for Transferring Corves or Boxes to or from Mine Cages, Hoists, and the like.
column13: 23,612. Berry, J. Oct. 29. Lifts.-Relates to apparatus for loading or unloading corves into or from cages or hoists at the tops or bottoms of shafts of coal mines or the like. The corves run down inclined rails by gravity towards stoppers or drop fences C, Fig. 1, which are caused to slide on fixed guiderods by means of two levers F, one on each side of the cage and operated together. One lever is connected by means of a link and bell-crank lever to the rod H of a slide valve, which admits steam or compressed air to a cylinder, thus forcing out a piston-rod I carrying a crosshead 0 and a pivoted fork P which engages an axle of a corve. The crosshead and fork are shown separately in Fig. 6. Jaws on the upper part of the crosshead are provided with an elongated hole to receive a shank on a second pair of jaws, which embrace the fork and through which the pivot passes. The crosshead is guided by slide bars, which are provided with spring or rubber buffers at the ends. The apparatus may be adapted for use where the length of the cage is at right-angles to the length of the corves, as shown in Fig. 7. Two foot-levers M, arranged one on each side of the cage, actuate the curved levers shown in Fig. 9, which press on tongues formed on the retaining-catches, and so unlock the corves from the cages. Two adjacent corves on separate pairs of rails are pushed simultaneously into the cage by extending the crossbead laterally and providing it with two forks.

Improvements in and applicable to Covers for Pneumatic Tyres.
column13: 2246. Berry, J. Jan. 29. Tread bands, projections, and surfaces. - Blocks of wood, metal, rubber, or other suitable material are held detachably in metal holders, which are secured in one or more rows, directly or by means of metal base-plates, to the cover of a pneumatic tyre or to a band thereon. In the form shown in Fig. 2, the holder 1 is in the form of a box, the bottom of which is riveted to the tyre or band, and the block 3 is secured therein by a pin 2 opposite an inclined side. In the form shown in Fig. 4, the holder comprises halves attached to the band or tyre, which may be separated to receive the block, the block being secured therein by inclined sides, grooves, projections, and, in some cases, by bolts, which may pass through the two parts of the block. In the form shown in Fig. 7, the holders are of ring form with inclined walls, and are secured to base-plates 15 by projections 18 engaging in recesses in a flange 16 on the plate and lugs 20, passing through slots in an opposite flange 17, screwed to the plates. The holders and blocks may be square, hexagonal, circular, or of other form. In the form shown in Fig. 9, they are shaped to give a continuous tread surface. The holders may be linked together.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the Lubrication of the Axles of Colliery Wagons, Tubs or Corves and the like.
column13: 26,727. Berry, J. Dec. 8. Air-escape valves; piston valves; tubular valves. -In connection with the automatic lubrication of the axle bearings of colliery wagons, tubs, or corves, &c., a lubricator is combined with a tipper, the lubricant being delivered by the motion of the tipper. One or more drums d are provided with air valves g and delivery spouts f. In the position shown in Fig. 1, the air valves are closed, but when the tipper is inverted, the valves open and allow the lubricant to pass from the spouts f to the axles of the corve &c. Preferably, the air valve comprises a piston h, Fig. 7, working in a bush i provided with ports j opening into the interior of the drum. The piston is carried by a screwed rod k provided with nuts l by which the amount of opening of the valve can be regulated according to requirement. Each spout may be provided with a self-closing device for delivering a measured quantity of the lubricant at each operation. The spout n, Fig. 10, slides within a part n, and is provided with ports o, p opening into a chamber s on the part r and into the drum respectively. As the tipper is turned, the spout slides to cover and uncover the ports ; the lubricant collected in the chamber s during the previous operation of the tipper is then delivered through the spout, and afterwards the chamber is again filled ready for the next operation of the tipper. According to the Provisional Specification, a tap, controlled by a gravity lever, may be applied to each spout.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Machines for Making Bricks, Tiles, and the like.
column13: 8743. Berry, J. April 6. Moulding bricks, tiles, &c.- Fig. shows in plan view a pugmill a and sliding mould plate c<1> for producing rough bricks, and Fig. 13 a vertical section of one of the presses for finishing the bricks. Cylindrical stems of the knives or curved blades b pass through holes in the square portion b<2> of the pug-mill shaft, and are secured by nuts b<3>. The mould plate c' has two apertures or moulds, and is moved backwards and forwards by cams to bring the empty mould opposite to the mouthpiece of the pugmill and the filled moulds opposite to the ejecting-plungers g, g<1>. These plungers are covered with flannel lubricated from an oil reservoir g*, and are reciprocated by cranks g<2>, a rocking shaft g<2>@,and cams on the sides of a spur-wheel, acting on rollers g<5>, g<7>. The ejected bricks fall on endless bands k, k<1>, and are transferred by push-plates k<3> to bottom plates m of the presses. The sides n<4> of the mould are hinged to a plate n' of the frame n<2>, and are opened outwards and closed by the up-and-down motion of a frame n<3>, which acts on inclined surfaces of the sides of the mould. The pressing-plunger n* and frames n<3> are reciprocated by cams on a shaft p<1>. The bottom plates m are raised and lowered by cams, and the carrier or push-plates are reciprocated by cams and rocking levers. The rough brick is slightly smaller than the finished brick, and the formation of the frog or indent by the pressing-plunger forces the clay outwards to the sides of the press box or mould. The pug-mill, cam, and working shafts are driven from a main shaft by toothed gearing, and a hand-wheel is provided for moving the parts to any required position for repairs &c.

Improvements in and relating to hatch covers of ships
column13: 830,356. Hatch covers. SHORT BROS. Ltd. Sept. 19, 1956, No. 28674/56. Class 113. A ship's hatch cover is adapted to be lifted and to be displaced in a direction parallel to a pair of walls of the hatch coaming. The hatch cover 1 has at least three mountings 11a attached to it by bolts 12. Each mounting has a nut 13 welded to it through which screws the jack 14. At the bottom of each jack there is a roller 17, grooved to run on rail 22 of deck 2, mounted in a fork member 18 which has a collar 19 rotatable relative to the head 20 of the jack. The hatch cover has a series of stiffeners 27 on the top, and a solid bar 6 welded to the bottom which enters the packing material 4, when in the closed position. Wing nuts on screws 9 fit slots in the hatch cover for fastening down. To remove the cover the fastenings 9 are released, the jacks oerated to lift the cover which is then pushed along the rails. Different types of jacks may be used, for example, one having a lateral projecting stub which is inserted in the recess of a mounting fixed to the cover or a ratchet type jack. Various arrangements of jacks may be employed, provided they support the cover in a substantially stable equilibrium, for example two jacks either side of the cover, two on one side and one in the other or one on each side and one in the middle of a third side.

column12: METHODS AND APPARATUS FOR STERILIZATION OF AIR AND OBJECTS
column13: A portable air sterilization apparatus includes a portable chamber forming an interior volume, a portable source for producing a single beam of collimated light energy, and a rotating beam redirector. The portable chamber includes a first end for introducing air into the chamber, a second end for permitting air to exit from the chamber, a transparent orifice through which a single beam of collimated light energy can be introduced into the interior volume of the chamber; and at least one reflective wall. The rotating beam redirector is adapted to rotate through a complete revolution about a rotational axis and to redirect the single beam of collimated light energy within the chamber during said revolution.

column13: A mold formed reaction container includes a lower portion having four sides forming an open top parallelepiped structure and an upper portion in the shape of a threaded hollow cylinder over which a cap may be screwed. The lower portion is inserted in a square opening of an automatic chemical analyzer so that two of the sides thereof are in a radiant energy path. The opening of the analyzer has two slot indentions removed from two opposite sides thereof and the lower portion of the container has two corresponding key extensions therefrom to insure the proper two sides of the container are placed in the energy path. Further, one of the sides of the container not having a key extension has a label on a portion thereof and that portion intersects and blocks a second radiant energy path through the opening in such a manner that the insertion of the container can be detected.

column12: Dispensed optical fibre links
column13: In an optical fibre dispenser, such as is used to dispense fibre into the environment as for the transmission of guidance commands to a remotely operated vehicle, a single coil is replaced by a series of coils, each of which is bypassed temporarily with a short-low-loss frangible link. By this method the Winding Increment of Attenuation of each coil is effectively "bypassed", enabling low power transmitter and receivers and in particular smaller diameter coils to be used. In one embodiment, four dispenser coils A, B, C, D have their fibres FA, FB, FC, FD joined in series enabling payout of the full fibre link to the effected. Each coil, except A, is by-passed by a parallel short low loss optical link LB, LC, LD, the joins being effected by Y-couplings YB1, 2; YC1, 2; and YD1, 2. Each link incorporates a local point BB, BC, BD such that tensile load on the link during dispensing of the fibre will break the link.

column13: 925,546. Valves. MAIN WATER HEATERS Ltd. Aug. 3, 1961 [Aug. 12, 1960], No. 28045/60. Class 135. [Also in Group XIII] The flow of water to an instantaneous heater is controlled by two valves, one responsive to water pressure and the other to the temperature of the water in the stream. The water supply fed at 15 passes through a port controlled by a valve member 19 which is connected to a diaphragm 10. Water then flows past a valve 27 and pipe 36 to the heated tubes, shown diagrammatically at 33. The diaphragm is subjected on one side to the water pressure downstream of the valve 19 and on the other side to a spring loading 44 and water pressure downstream of the valve 27 fed through a small pipe 25 whereby a constant pressure drop is maintained across the valve 27. The valve 27 is adjusted by a bellows 32 filled with a liquid and connected to a bulb 30 preferably located near the heated water outlet, e.g. in the last limb of a zig-zag arrangement of heating tube. The diaphragm may also control a gas valve 42 supplying the burners. A stop 39 may be provided to limit the closure of valve 27 to allow a small flow, when the heater is cold, to open the gas valve.

The upper fixing member may be incorporated in a knee joint and the lower in an ankle joint. The whole device may be incorporated in a thigh section. The ball parts may be carried by the fixing members. As shown, the load-bearing member comprises tubular sections 1, 2 and 3 which are threaded telescopically. The lower fixing member comprises plates 16, 17 slidable relatively to one another. Plate 16 has a tapered slot 18 in which the tapered neck, attached to ball 15 in split bushes 8 and 9, is slidable and may be secured by a bolt. The position of plates 16 and 17 may be secured by bolts 21.

column13: In apparatus comprising needles (l0), a mandrel (ll) and electrostatically charged plates (l2, l3, l4 and l5), variation of the electrostatic potential on the mandrel (ll) and the plates (l2, l3, l4 and l5) produces variation of the fibrous structure produced. In general, where the mandrel (ll) is significantly more attractive to the fibres, a microstructure of fibres of substantially uniform diameter is produced, these fibres being generally randomly orientated. Where the voltages on the mandrel (ll) and on the plates (l3 and l5) are varied to lessen the attraction of the mandrel (ll) relative to the plates (l3, l5) the fibrous structure is varied to produce fibres of a larger diameter than the original micro fibrous structure, this having a significant effect on characteristics of the fibrous structure.

column12: Information Recorded with Coded Ink.
column13: 1,170,965. Luminescent materials. AMERICAN CYANAMID CO. 19 Jan., 1967 [9 Feb., 1966], No. 2971/67. Heading C4S. [Also in Division G4] A record such as a cheque or card has symbols, e.g. legible characters, recorded thereon by means of a combination of at least one material which fluoresces under ultraviolet radiation and at least one material reflecting any or none of the visible colours red, green and blue. The symbols may be sensed by spatially separating the fluoresecent and visible portions of a symbol and simultaneously irradiating the respective portions with ultraviolet and white light, there being an appropriate number of photodetectors responding to the various fluorescent and reflected colours. Alternatively, the two symbol portions may overlap, and the symbol is sequentially illuminated with ultraviolet and white light. In this case, it may be possible to use the same detectors for both portions, the threshold level for sensing visible marks being higher than that for sensing fluorescent marks. The illumination sources may be covered by shutters as the record is intermittently advanced between successive symbols. The fluorescent materials may be 4,5-diphenylimidazolone-2 and lanthanide ion chelates, e.g. chelates of europium, terbium and samarium. Optical fibre light guides may be provided to the photodetectors.

column13: Methods and apparatus are described for the positive identification of an individual wishing to undertake a financial transaction over a telecommunication medium. Financial, fingerprint and image data of an individual are encrypted and stored on a smart card. A person offering the card for a financial transaction has a fingerprint taken from which an encryption key is determined and used to decrypt the fingerprint and image data held on the card. If the fingerprint data obtained from the person matches the fingerprint data of the individual stored on the card, then the image stored on the card is displayed for further identification of the person. Devices are described which enable this identification method to be used in conjunction with an EFTPOS terminal or similar.

A stream of fuel gas is passed through at least one vessel containing ferric oxide, and a second stream of gas containing a constituent for addition to the fuel gas together with oxygen is passed through at least one vessel containing previously sulphided ferric oxide and the two streams of gas are subsequently admixed. column13: IMPROVEMENTS IN ELECTROSTATICALLY PRODUCED STRUCTURES AND METHODS OF MANUFACTURING THEREOF. In apparatus comprising needles (10), a mandrel (11) and electrostatically charged plates (12, 13, 14 and 15), variation of the electrostatic potential on the mandrel (11) and the plates (12, 13, 14 and 15) produces variation of the fibrous structure produced. In general, where the mandrel (11) is significantly more attractive to the fibres, a microstructure of fibres of substantially uniform diameter is produced, these fibres being generally randomly orientated. Where the voltages on the mandrel (11) and on the plates (13 and 15) are varied to lessen the attraction of the mandrel (11) relative to the plates (13, 15) the fibrous structure is varied to produce fibres of a larger diameter than the original micro fibrous structure, this having a significant effect on characteristics of the fibrous structure.

column12: Improvements in artificial legs
column13: 886,569. Artificial knee Joints. VESSA Ltd. Dec. 15, 1960 [Dec. 16, 1959], No. 42864/59. Class 81 (2). A knee joint for an artificial leg has means by which, on returning to a straight position, the movement is free over the greater part of its range, but has a controlled resistance applied to it over a small angle before the straight position is reached. The control is effected hydraulically and the joint comprises a radial vane 8, mounted on an axle 4 and rotated within a cylindrical casing 1 by the shin member, the casing being attached to the thigh. The casing is filled with oil and, over the greater part of the movement of the vane 8, oil is free to pass around its outer end. Towards the end of its movement, however, the vane passes adjacent to an arcuate plate 14 which causes the oil to pass through orifices 15 and one-way valves 16, causing a slight resistance to the freedom of movement. Finally, over the last few degrees of straightening the knee, the orifices bear against and are closed by spring- loaded balls 17. column12: AIR PURIFICATION SYSTEM
column13: This invention relates to an air purification apparatuses and methods for air purification. The air purification apparatuses pass air through energy beams that form one or more fields of energy within a chamber to produce an outflow of sterilized air. In some aspects, a charge generation system is implemented to repel particles from the chamber walls. In some aspects, the fields of energy extend across substantially an entirety of the cross sectional area of the interior volume of the chamber and longitudinally within the chamber. column13: 1,036,749. Waveguides. MARCONI CO. Ltd. July 9, 1964 [July 25, 1963], No. 29590/63. Heading H1W. The waveguide transition of Specification 805,510, for transforming the TE 01 rectangular mode to the TE 01 circular mode, improved in that it is dimensioned in such a manner that the guided wavelength is constant over the length of the transition within the transmission frequency band. The known transition comprises a first section a in which a rectangular input end 5 is transformed by a double taper to a rectangular output end lying at right angles to the input end and having a major dimension twice that of the input end. This is followed by a section b transforming between a rectangular input end and a symmetrical cruciform output end and by a section c in which the cruciform section is transformed to a circular section. The first section may be improved by spacing the start of one of the tapers from the end of the section, e.g. at the position 6, whereby it extends over three-quarters the length of the section. Both tapers may be modified in this way and the tapers may be curved, e.g. according to a cos<SP>2</SP> curve. The first section is preferably three wavelengths long. A further method of improving the first section consists in so dimensioning the L-shaped symmetrical halves of the transition that they have a constant cut-off frequency at any section preferably equal to the cut-off frequency of the initial section 5. The dimensions of the cruciform section are such that the width d (minor dimension) of the arms is smaller than the value given by the equation # h =d.2#2, where # h is the free-space wavelength corresponding to the highest operating frequency. Preferably, the diameter of the circular output end of the third section is made greater than the longer side of the output end of the first section and this increase of dimension may be achieved either by a progressive increase extending over the whole transition or over only the third section.

column13: A mold resistant structural drywall track system is disclosed. In one embodiment, the track system comprises a base section, lower side wall, lateral support, and upper side wall. The lateral support supports wall material, such as gypsum board, above the floor to prevent moisture from wicking into the gypsum board. Additionally, ventilation and drainage means are included to allow for ventilation and drainage of moisture that may collect behind a wall. The base section, lower side wall, and lateral support generally form a cavity with the lower side wall substantially perpendicular to the base section. Preferably, the lower side wall is in the same plane as the finished wall surface above, thereby preventing damage to gypsum board, including any rubber base or resilient material installed over the gypsum board. The drywall track system may be employed with metal stud structures as well as wood frame structures.

column13: A computer-implemented method for providing a reward based on a price differential for a product is described. The method is implemented using a computing device in communication with one or more memory devices. The method includes receiving, by the computing device, a reward determination request message including an identification of a first merchant and product data for a product purchased by a cardholder from the first merchant. The method also includes determining a location of the first merchant, determining, using the one or more memory devices, the price differential between a first price for the product from the first merchant and at least a second price for the product from at least a second merchant within a predetermined geographic distance of the first merchant, and applying a reward to a cardholder account associated with the cardholder, wherein the reward is based on the price differential.

column13: Aqueous dispersions of terpolymers are made by emulsifying a mixture of 80 per cent of vinylidene chloride, between 0.1 and 2.5 per cent of an acidic ethylenic compound and acrylonitrile in an aqueous medium containing a modifying compound of the formula <FORM:0674728/IV (a)/1> wherein R and R1 are hydrogen or a hydrocarbon radical, e.g. methyl isobutyl ketone, and, as dispersing agent, 3 to 6 per cent, based on the mixture of monomers, of a water-dispersible alkyl sulphate, containing 8 to 18 carbon atoms in the alkyl group, e.g. sodium lauryl sulphate, sodium cetyl sulphate, sodium octadecyl sulphate and "Teepol" (Registered Trade Mark) and subjecting to polymerizing temperatures, e.g. 40 DEG C. The acidic ethylenic compound may be citraconic or itaconic acid or anhydrides thereof, mesaconic acid, acrylic acid or a mixture of acid anhydrides comprising citraconic and itaconic anhydrides formed by distilling citric acid. Catalysts, e.g. ammonium persulphate and activators, e.g. sodium metabisulphite, may be present. The product may be isolated by coagulation, e.g. by addition of alkali metal or ammonium sulphate, evaporation or electrophoresis. Films of regenerated cellulose, polyvinyl alcohol, cellulose esters or ethers, gelatin and casein may be coated with the terpolymer in aqueous dispersion or in solution in methyl ethyl ketone or a mixture thereof with toluene or tetrahydrofurane. Specifications 633,645, 649,719 and 654,342, [Group VIII], are referred to.

column12: Improvements relating to Automatic Tracking Apparatus.
column13: 1,177,641. Optical direction-finding; transistor gating circuits. ELECTRIC & MUSICAL INDUSTRIES Ltd. 26 Jan., 1962 [3 Feb., 1961], No. 4254/61. Headings H3T and H4D. Apparatus for tracking a radiating bodymoving relative to the apparatus comprises a first lattice of elongated parallel radiationsensitive elements, a second lattice of elongated parallel radiation-sensitive elements at right angles to the first, means for focusing radiation on the two lattices from substantially the same point of view, first and second sampling means for sampling the elements of the two lattices respectively in predetermined manner to determine which, if any, of the elements is sensitized by radiation, and output means responsive to the sampling means to produce an output signal dependent on the direction of the radiating body relative to the tracking apparatus. Referring to Fig. 1, infra-red radiation emitted by a target is sampled by a mechanical chopper (not shown) and focused by a Schmitt optical system 1 on to two lattices 2 of infra-red sensitive cells carried by the missile. (Only one lattice 2 and its circuit is shown in Fig. 1). Each cell is scanned in turn by a series of switches or gates 3 controlled by a counter 4, and only that.cell on which radiation is focused will produce an output, the particular cell being determined by the angular position of the radiation source. This output is applied to a high-pass filter 5, amplifier 6 and blanking circuit 7 which cuts out components of the switching pulses; after passing through amplifier 9 the signal is detected at 10 to .reduce the A.C. component due to the mechanical chopper and applied to a Schmitt trigger circuit 11 which provides a fixed output whenever the signal rises above a predetermined value. The switches 3 are normally operated sequentially by a ring counter 4 which is driven by pulses from the counter control unit 8 via the counter driver 12. The counter control unit 8 produces driving pulses only when no signal is produced by unit 11. When a signal appears, e.g. from cell " x," the counter control unit 8, and hence the counter 4, stops and cell " x " remains connected to the output line as long as it is producing a signal. If the signal disappears, the unit 8 produces a drive pulse which stops the counter 4 in the direction in which it was last moving, for example to the (x + 1)<SP>th</SP> stage; if there is still no signal the unit 8 in conjunction with reversal unit 13 rapidly reverses the counter 4 two stages to the (x - 1)<SP>th</SP> stage and if there is still no signal the counter proceeds to count in this direction. The counter 4 is connected to a digital to analogue converter 14 whereby the count number at any instant is converted to a voltage proportional to the coordinate value. The signal from 14 is applied to a computer (not shown) and may, if desired, be gated into the computer by the " target present " signal from unit 11. A second input to the computer is derived from the second lattice to give the position of the target relative to the missile in two directions at right angles, and from these two values the computer calculates the angle of sight and its rate of change and hence the optimum moment of detonation. Blanking circuit.-The blanking circuit, Fig. 2, comprises a transistor T connected across a tuned circuit C 3 L 4 of which the centre tap of the coil L 4 is earthed to A.C. When T is cut off the coil L 4 behaves as an autotransformer and the signal is simply inverted in passing from the input amplifier 6 to the output amplifier 9. When T conducts the signal is fed to both halves of coil L 4 simultaneously and cancels out. Ring counter.-The ring counter shown in Fig. 3 comprises a number of stages each including a four-layer PNPN semi-conductor diode S connected to one of the lines ABC which are energized in sequence by means not shown. The potential applied to lines ABC is insufficient to cause conduction through a diode but sufficient to maintain conduction. When the circuit is switched on means are provided to ensure that one and only one diode will conduct (for example a non-linear impedance may be connected between the negative potential source and the junction of resistances RC1, RC2, RC3 ...). If line B is energized and diode S2 is conducting, the condensers C associated with diodes S1 and S3 are charged through diodes DB; this charge enables diode S1 or S3 to conduct if line B is de-energized and line A or C energized. Thus the stages can be energized in sequence in either direction according to the sequence of energization of lines AB and C.

column12: Improvements in and relating to textile cords for tyre reinforcement
column13: 889,326. Yarns and threads. COURTAULDS Ltd. Nov. 11, 1958 [Nov. 12, 1957], No. 35178/57. Class 120(3) [Also in Group XXXIV] A composite cord for use as circumferential reinforcement of the crowns of tyres consists of a "destructible" textile core around which is helically wound a tyre cord. The core, and consequently the composite cord, has a high initial modulus but the breaking extension of the core is less than the increase in the circumference of the base of the tread of the tyre occasioned by the shaping thereof. The remanent cord in the finished tyre has a high initial modulus. The core may be a staple fibre yarn of cotton and/or viscose rayon or continuous filaments, e.g. bulked, yarn and the helically wound cord may be a high tenacity, continuous filament, rayon, nylon or polyethylene terephthalate yarn. The tyre cord may be initially over-twisted and then back-twisted during the winding on the core so that the final fully extended cord has twist which is normal in tyre cords. Specification 776,728 is referred to.

column12: Dermatological treatment apparatus
column13: A dermatological treatment platform comprises an actively Q-switched laser and an intense pulsed light source with a power supply 10 having an electrical energy source, a captive energy store 24 for receiving energy from the energy source, a power outlet 26, and an electronically controlled switch 30 that can selectively connect the energy store to the power outlet connection for delivery to a light source. The power supply further includes timing circuitry 22 that can operate the electronically controlled switch and an optical switch within a device 12 connected to the power supply. The capacitive energy source is charged in use to a potential suitable for operation of both the laser and the intense pulsed light source, typically less than 500V. Thus both laser and intense pulsed light treatment can be offered without incurring the expense of two power supplies.

column12: Lighting control system and method for communication of short messaging
column13: An area lighting control system is provided for a light fixture and occupancy sensors. In a pairing mode, the occupancy sensors transmit messages with respective unique addresses to the light fixture, which identifies an associated sensor network. Upon lapsing of the pairing mode, an operating mode follows during which the sensors transmit output signals representative of occupancy in the area, and the light fixture regulates respective light sources based on an occupancy state determined according to output signals received from the associated network. The output signals are transmitted according to pseudo-random time intervals in order to reduce wireless transmission collisions, and only upon determining no occupancy in the defined area. When signals are received from all sensors in the network during a predetermined time period, the light fixture dims the light sources, whereas otherwise the light fixture operates the light sources at full lighting state.

Improvements in and connected with Mechanical Stokers.
column13: 2068. Phythian, J., and Berry, A. E. Feb. 2. Mechanical stoking; fire-bars and grates; linings.-Fuel is fed to a reciprocating grate of special construction by means of a special form of rotary feeder located in the base of a hopper. A protective, metallic, removable lining is provided at the mouth of the furnace. As shown in Fig. 2, the fuel hopper c is provided with a bridge c" with inclined sides to direct the fuel to openings c<1> which are controlled by a slide e actuated by a screwed shaft e<11>, working in nuts upon the slide and rotated by bevel-gear g<1>. The fuel is fed to the furnace by the rotary drum i, which is provided with blades i<1> of the form shown in Fig. 1. A distributing . plate f, kept cool by water and provided with ribs, directs the fuel on to the coking-plate j, which may also be ribbed. Motion is given to the rotary drum i by worm gearing mounted on the vertical shaft l and drum shaft. The shaft l receives motion from worm gear and spur gear n' driven from a shaft n<11> provided with pulleys n<111>. The vertical shaft l is also provided with worm gearing for giving motion to the cam shaft w, which is provided with cams w<1>, w<11> for giving a reciprocating motion to the fire-bars. The latter are arranged in two sets or series r, r', Fig. 4, those in one set or section alternating with those in the other section. The bars in each section are connected by crossbars s, s' secured to their respective side bars t, t<1>, which are provided at their front ends with suitable projections u, u<1>, u<11>, u<111> and recesses v, v<1>, Fig. 5. The cam-surface w<1> is in advance of the cam-surface w<11>, and, during each revolution, strikes the shoulders u on the side-bars t and moves the latter towards the front of the furnace, while the cam w<11>, subsequently, by striking the shoulders u<1>, moves the bars t<1> in the same direction. The backward movement of the bars r is effected by the cam w<1>engaging with the feet u<11> on the bars t. The feet u<11> are also provided with lateral projections, as shown in Fig. 6, which, as the bars t move backwards, engage the feet u<111>on the bars t<1>, whereupon the two sets of bars move back together. The fire-bars are stepped and inclined as shown and ride upon a roller x to facilitate motion. The protective metallic lining for the furnace mouth is shown in Figs. 2 and 3. Each side lining comprises two suitably-shaped castings or blocks o, o' of metal, one o of which is provided with longitudinal grooves p having lateral extensions at rightangles to receive projections p<1> upon the block o'. Each block may be grooved, in which case a bolt with a flange or the like is employed to enter the grooves and hold the blocks together, and also secure them to the boiler front. The blocks may also be secured to the furnace front by bolts q. Additional blocks o<11> may also be arranged at the crown of the furnace mouth.

column12: Air samplers
column13: An air sampler for use in analyzing biological or other analytes, comprizes an airflow chamber having an air inlet and an air outlet. An extract from an air mover draws ambient air in through the inlet, and then through the chamber, to discharge it back to atmosphere by way of an outlet. The airflow chamber houses a cyclone air/liquid separator through which the inflowing air is caused to pass. An injector introduces liquid into air flowing through the air inlet. The cyclone separator extracts this liquid and any entrained particles therein and discharges it from the airflow chamber, initially by way of a duct, where it is then conveyed to a collection vessel, by way of a three channel peristaltic pump, and a duct. The collection vessel is housed within a Peltier-cooled holder to maintain the contents of the vessel within the 2-8 degree Celsius range.

column12: Dermatological treatment apparatus
column13: A dermatological treatment platform is disclosed that incorporates an actively Q-switched laser and intense pulsed light source. The platform comprises: a power supply having an electrical energy source, a capacitive energy store for receiving energy from the energy source, a power outlet, and an electronically controlled switch that can selectively connect the energy store to the power outlet connection for delivery to a light source. The power supply further includes timing circuitry that can operate the electronically controlled switch and an optical switch within a device connected to the power supply. The capacitative energy source is charged in use to a potential suitable for operation of both the laser and the intense pulsed light source, typically less than 500V. Thus, a practitioner can offer both laser and intense pulsed light treatment without incurring the expense of two power supplies.

column12: Method and apparatus for estimating speed profile for vehicle and motor vehicle comprising the system
column13: The present invention relates to a method and a system for estimating a speed profile for a vehicle, and a motor vehicle comprising the system. The vehicle has a steering wheel and comprises a map database with at least one record. The record presents at least one path, the vehicle being located on the path, and the path presenting a plurality of position points. A portion of the points present adjacent points defining a path section. The vehicle further comprises a locator device communicatively coupled to the map database. The method comprises the steps of determining of the location of the vehicle and matching the location with a first point of the points on the path, identifying an approaching path section point and estimating a path section speed profile based on map data.

As shown in Fig. 1, a supplementary movement is given to the differential gear train of the registering mechanism by pawls h, i carried by a bar g connected to a plunger c which is reciprocated by a crank d and connecting-rod e through a spring f. The extent of movement of the plunger c is controlled by a curved striking-plate b carried by a lever p connected by a link to a sliding member o. The sliding member o is connected through a lever n to a diaphragm a and by a chain q to a quadrant r secured to an arm s provided with a weight t. An increase in the pressure of the gas acts through the diaphragm a and connected parts to move the striking- plate b and to move the weight t angularly to increase its leverage. In a modification, the weight t is carried by the striking-plate b. Specification 7727/11 is referred to. The Provisional Specification also states that a piston under the influence of the gas pressure may cause a wheel to mesh with any one of a series of wheels or with parts of a wheel with numbers of teeth removed at different points.

To avoid this, two cylinders A, A' are employed. The worm D, driven by ratchet mechanism, is mounted on a lever C and can be moved into engagement with either of the nuts B, B<1> to cause the descent of the corresponding piston. The lever C is connected with the plug F of a three-way cock so that whichever piston is descending the corresponding cylinder must communicate with the delivery pipe.

column13: 1,149,387. Pipe joints. YORKSHIRE IMPERIAL METALS Ltd. 14 Sept., 1966 [14 Sept., 1965], No. 39172/65. Heading F2G. [Also in Division B3] Method of welding a metal tube 1 in an aperture in a plate 2, wherein the distance between the outer wall of the tube and the wall of the aperture increases towards the adjacent free end of the tube, comprises using an explosive charge 5 to force an inert insert 6 against the tube-bore. At least part of the length of the aperture may be tapered, or the outer diameter of the tube-end. The explosive 5 may have a detonation velocity greater than 120% of the velocity of sound in the metal of the tube or tube-plate, whichever has the higher sonic velocity. The aperture-portion 4 may follow an exponential curve or a double taper, and the short end of the tube may project beyond the plate 2 and be severed over the radiused or angled edges at the end of the aperture. To achieve a good metallurgical bond between the tube and plate, surface oxides and grease are removed before assembly. The density of the wax and sawdust plug 6 may be varied along its length, and a number of tube-ends may be secured simultaneously. Tubes of aluminiumbrass may be secured to a brass or coppernickel plate, or a copper-nickel tube may be secured to a copper-nickel or brass plate.

column12: ANTI-PERSPIRANT COMPOSITION
column13: The invention relates to use of chitosan or a salt thereof in an anti-perspirant composition as an anti-perspirant ingredient. Current anti-perspirants are based on aluminium, but inorganic salts have the effect of leaving white patches on clothes. Additionally there is a perceived health risk associated with aluminium The current approach is to reduce the amount of aluminium in antiperspirants or to use additional metal salts such as those of zirconium. However, this approach tends to lower the efficacy of the formulation and hence prove more expensive. Zirconium-based antiperspirants tend to leave yellow patches on clothes. Use of chitosan or a salt thereof in an anti-perspirant composition as an anti-perspirant ingredient is provided, wherein the chitosan or salt thereof has a degree of acetylation of 0-15, preferably 0-12, most preferably 0-10%, wherein the chitosan or salt thereof is either in an anhydrous form or dissolved in water at a pH of no more than 6.0, preferably no more than 5.5, most preferably no more than 5.0.

A moulding-machine comprises a vertically - movable blowing - head above a fixed framework supporting a mould or core-box, said framework including means for effecting horizontal opening movement of the box, a finished - mould or core stripped from the box upon opening movement thereof being removed from the machine through an opening in the bottom of the framework. The core-box 34, 35, is opened and closed by a double-acting piston as described in Specification 819,475, which is referred to, and the finished cores are removed therefrom by collecting means 14 comprising a cradle 36 vertically movable by a cylinder 40. A shoot 42 picks the core trom the cradle during its downward movement, and transfers it to conveying means 15. The main element of an artificial limb comprises a tube 30 telescopically adjustable in end tubes 31, 32, each end tube being connected by a releasable ball and socket joint 18, 28 to a rod 17 threaded in one end plate 21 which is slidable in a dovetail slot in the second end plate 22. The discs 13 to 16 are rotated by tommy bars 20 to porvide the desired angle between the end plates 21, 22 and the axis of the limb and the end plates adjusted relative to one another. column12: CEMENT-BLOCK MACHINE.
A METHOD FOR INTEGRATING STRUCTURED DATA AND STRING DATA ON A TEXT PROCESSING SYSTEM
column13: An improved method is disclosed for operating an interactive text processing system to integrate and process DP type structured field data and WP type text or string field data in the same record. The method involves displaying to the text processing system operator a menu of data type codes selectable through a keyboard for defining the types of data fields in a record. In response to operator selected field types, structured fields of fixed length (41) and address pointers of fixed length for the string fields are established for the records. When the data is keyed in, the structured fields are concatenated with the string field address pointers and the text data (43), including format control codes, is stored at a system selected address in a variable length section of an auxiliary storage device such as a disk file. The structured field data is displayed or printed under control of the field length definitions and the string field data is displayed or printed under control of the address pointer and imbedded format control codes.

column12: Enhanced link 16 detection with interference mitigation
column13: A method for implementing interference mitigation in wireless network such as a Link (16) network does not require interference recognition and does not degrade signal detection even in the absence of interference. An unmitigated correlation score is obtained by correlating received, unmitigated preamble symbols with expected symbols. At least one of the input signals is also correlated after mitigation to obtain a mitigated signal. A mitigated correlation score is obtained from the mitigated signals, and a mixed correlation score is obtained by combining mitigated and unmitigated signals. A signal is detected if any of the correlation scores exceeds a corresponding threshold. Embodiments use the unmitigated correlation for subsequent message time of arrival determination if the unmitigated correlation score is above its detection threshold. In embodiments, mitigation is applied to only one of the message frequencies. Implementation of the disclosed method does not require excessive additional electronic resources.

column12: Combustion System with Panel Fuel Injector
column13: The present disclosure is directed to an annular combustion system. The annular combustion system includes an inner liner and an outer liner that define therebetween an annulus that circumscribes a centerline of the combustion system. The annulus includes a plurality of primary combustion zones defined at an upstream end thereof and further defines a plurality of secondary combustion zones downstream of the primary combustion zones. The annular combustion system further includes a plurality of fuel nozzles where at least one fuel nozzle discharges a combustible mixture into a respective primary combustion zone of the plurality of primary combustion zones. A plurality of panel fuel injectors is disposed between adjacent fuel nozzles. The plurality of panel fuel injectors extends in an axially downstream direction so as to separate adjacent primary combustion zones. Each panel fuel injector discharges a combustible mixture into at least one secondary combustion zone.

column12: Report generation control system for text processing machines.
column13: A report generation control system for operating a text processor to produce output reports containing inter-report summary data from data processing-type files. The system is compatible with text pagination functions and is useable by a text entry/revision operator with no programming skills. The system permits the operator to describe the desired report by keying an example page of the report in the exact desired format and then editing the example page by replacing the required variable file data examples with descriptive instructions such as (FRP) (DCG) (RCD) and by inserting summary instructions such as (CGS) (FRS). The system scans the edited example page for instructions, breaks it down into logical components and compiles the components into program routines which will produce the desired output renort.

column12: MAGNETIC SEALING ARRANGEMENT FOR A TURBOMACHINE
column13: Sealing arrangements (201) and turbomachines are provided. A sealing arrangement (201) includes a transition duct (44) having an upstream end (46) and a downstream end (48). The transition duct (44) includes an aft frame (100) that circumferentially surrounds the downstream end (48) of the transition duct (44). A stage one nozzle (500) is spaced apart from the aft frame (100) and defines a gap (202) therebetween. A sealing assembly (400) extends across the gap (202) and is magnetically coupled to both the aft frame (100) and the stage one nozzle (500). The sealing assembly (400) includes a first magnet (402) coupled to the aft frame (100) and a second magnet (404) coupled to the stage one nozzle (500). The sealing assembly (400) further includes a shell (428) that is coupled to and at least partially surrounds the first magnet (402) and the second magnet (404).

The unified head end (200) includes a first fuel nozzle (202) and a second fuel nozzle (204) disposed at a forward end portion of the combustion liner (110). column12: Staged fuel and air injection in combustion system of gas turbine
column13: The invention relates to staged fuel and air injection in a combustion system of a gas turbine, and concretely relates to a gas turbine. The gas turbine includes: a combustor coupled to a turbine that define a working fluid flowpath; a compressor discharge cavity; a staged injection system that includes the forward injector and a staged injector; a stator blade positioned extending across the working fluid flowpath between an inboard sidewall and an outboard sidewall. A one-way continuous coolant flowpath includes: an intake section that comprises an upstream port connected to the compressor discharge cavity and a downstream port formed through one of the inboard and outboard sidewalls; an outtake section that comprises a downstream port connected to the staged injector and an upstream port formed through the other one of the inboard and outboard sidewalls; and a cooling circuit extending through an interior of the airfoil of the stator blade and connecting to the downstream port of the intake section and the upstream port of the outtake section.

column12: System and method for producing hydrogen rich fuel
column13: A system for providing hydrogen enriched fuel includes first and second gas turbines. The second gas turbine receives a fuel from a fuel supply and portion of compressed working fluid from the first gas turbine and produces a reformed fuel, and a fuel skid provides fluid communication between a turbine in the second gas turbine and a combustor in the first gas turbine. A method for providing hydrogen enriched fuel includes diverting a portion of a first compressed working fluid from a first compressor to a second compressor and providing a second compressed working fluid from the second compressor. column13: A system for removing long-chain and short-chain per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) from contaminated water using a regenerable anion exchange resin includes at least one first anion exchange resin vessel configured to receive a flow of water contaminated with long and short-chain PFAS compounds. The at least one first anion exchange resin vessel includes a first regenerable anion exchange resin therein having a high affinity for long-chain PFAS compounds configured such that a majority of the long-chain PFAS compounds sorb to the first regenerable anion exchange resin to remove a majority of the long-chain PFAS compounds from the contaminated water and produce a flow of water having a majority of the long-chain PFAS compounds removed. column12: Radially Stacked Fuel Injection Module for a Segmented Annular Combustion System
column13: The present disclosure is directed to a radially stacked fuel injection module for a segmented annular combustion system. The fuel injection module includes a bundled tube fuel nozzle portion and a plurality of fuel injection lances. In one instance, a first set of fuel injection lances and a second set of fuel injection lances share a housing with the bundled tube fuel nozzle. The first and second sets of fuel injection lances are radially stacked, each set of lances being in communication with a respective injector fuel plenum. The fuel injection lances deliver fuel to a respective premixing channel formed between the side walls of an integrated combustor nozzle, an aft end of which defines a turbine nozzle. In another instance, the bundled tube fuel nozzle may be provided as a radially inner fuel nozzle and a radially outer fuel nozzle, each with a respective bundled tube fuel plenum.

column13: 1,110,123. Protective arrangements. J. STONE & CO. (DEPTFORD) Ltd. 19 April, 1966 [26 April, 1965], No. 17401/65. Heading H2K. An arrangement for protecting semi-conductor apparatus comprises a thyristor 3 connected across the supply to the apparatus and a Zener diode 4 or other device connected to the apparatus and responsive to overvoltage conditions to apply a control signal to the thyristor to render it conducting to short-circuit the apparatus. A fuse 7 is then blown, or an automatic circuit-breaker is operated, by the shortcircuit current to interrupt the supply to the apparatus. As shown, the Zener diode 4 is connected in series with a resistor 5 across the supply to the apparatus 1 and, in the event of overvoltage, conducts. The voltage across the resistor 5 is applied to the gate of the thyristor 3 through a variable resistor 6 to render the thyristor 3 conducting, a slight delay being provided by capacitors 9 to prevent undesired operation under transient conditions. Should the supply be alternating current, then diodes 10, 11 are connected as shown. Figs. 2 and 3 (not shown), illustrate the application of the arrangement to the field circuits of a D.C. generator and an alternator. By providing a further Zener diode 4 and resistor 5 the arrangement may be connected to provide overcurrent protection. Reference has been directed by the Comptroller to Specification 1,005,261.

column12: System und Verfahren zum Produzieren wasserstoffreichen Brennstoffes.
column13: Ein System (10) zum Bereitstellen von mit Wasserstoff angereichertem Brennstoff schliesst erste und zweite Gasturbinen (12, 14) ein. Die zweite Gasturbine (14) empfängt einen Teil (34) eines komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (30) von der ersten Gasturbine (12) und produziert einen reformierten Brennstoff (42), und eine Brennstoffschiene (20) stellt eine Strömungsverbindung zwischen einer Turbine (44) in der zweiten Gasturbine (14) und einem Brenner (24) in der ersten Gasturbine (12) bereit. Ein Verfahren zum Bereitstellen von mit Wasserstoff angereichertem Brennstoff schliesst das Ableiten eines Teiles (34) eines ersten komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (30) von einem ersten Verdichter (22) zu einem zweiten Verdichter (36) und das Bereitstellen eines zweiten komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (38) durch den zweiten Verdichter (36) ein. Das Verfahren schliesst weiter das Vermischen eines Brennstoffes (18) mit dem zweiten komprimierten Arbeitsfluid (38) in einem Reformer (40), um einen reformierten Brennstoff (42) zu produzieren, das Leiten des reformierten Brennstoffes (42) durch eine zweite Turbine (44), um den reformierten Brennstoff (42) zu kühlen, und das Verbinden der zweiten Turbine (44) mit dem zweiten Verdichter (36) ein, sodass die zweite Turbine (44) den zweiten Verdichter (36) antreibt.

SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR PRODUCING HYDROGEN RICH FUEL
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a system for supplying hydrogen enriched fuel.SOLUTION: A system includes first and second gas turbines. The second gas turbine receives a fuel from a fuel supply source and portion of compressed working fluid from the first gas turbine and produces a reformed fuel, and a fuel skid provides fluid communication between a turbine in the second gas turbine and a combustor in the first gas turbine. A method for supplying hydrogen enriched fuel includes a step of diverting a portion of a first compressed working fluid from a first compressor to a second compressor and a step of supplying a second compressed working fluid from the second compressor. Mixing a first portion of a compressed fuel with the second compressed working fluid in a reformer to produce a reformed fuel, flowing a second portion of the compressed fuel to a second turbine for cooling, and flowing the reformed fuel through the second turbine to cool the reformed fuel.

undwobei die Zapfluft (56), die in das sekundäre Verbrennungssystem (58) strömt, mit dem aus dem wenigstens einen Brennstoffinjektor (76) abgegebenen Brennstoff vermischt wird, um ein Luft/Brennstoff-Gemisch zu bilden.

column12: MULTI-TUBE LATE LEAN INJECTOR
column13: A micromixer injector includes a fuel plenum to receive a supply of fuel. A plurality of premixing tubes extend through the fuel plenum. Each tube has a plurality of fuel holes formed therein to receive the supply of fuel for mixing with air in the tube. The micromixer has a tapering profile such that an overall inlet area of the plurality of premixing tubes on an upstream face of the micromixer is larger than an overall outlet area of the plurality of premixing tubes on a downstream face such that the plurality of premixing tubes are relatively spaced-apart at the upstream face and more densely packed at the downstream face. Additionally, an air inlet of each tube has a first geometrical shape and the outlet of each tube has a second geometrical shape that is different from the first geometrical shape.

Three-dimensional workspace interactive display having browsing viewpoints for navigation and work viewpoints for user-object interactive non-navigational work functions with automatic switching to browsing viewpoints upon completion of work functions
column13: A system, method and computer program are provided for facilitating viewer navigation within a virtual reality three-dimensional workspace containing functional three-dimensional objects. The viewer has the capability of navigating towards such three-dimensional functional objects and interacting with them functionally in specific tasks. Such specific tasks often require a fairly narrow viewpoint to provide close viewer interaction with the object in the specific task. The present invention provides a means for facilitating the viewer's navigation along his desired or planned path after he has completed a specific task relationship with a particular selected object. Means are provided for monitoring the task specific relationship of the viewer with the object and as soon as a determination is made that the viewer has completed his task, the system automatically changes the viewpoint of the viewer from the task specific viewpoint to the optimum browsing or navigation viewpoint with respect to the viewer's current viewpoint so that the viewer can proceed further in his navigation.

column12: Method for integrating structured data and string data on a text processing system
column13: An improved method is disclosed for operating an interactive text processing system to integrate and process DP (data processing) type structured field data and WP (word or text processing) type text or string field data in the same record. The method involves displaying to the text processing system operator a menu of data type codes selectable through a keyboard for defining the types of data fields in a record. In response to operator selected field types, structured fields of fixed length and address pointers of fixed length for the string fields are established for the records. When the data is keyed in, the structured fields are concatenated with the address pointers for the string fields, and the text data, including format control codes, is stored at a system selected address on an auxiliary storage device such as a disk file. The structured field data is displayed or printed under control of the field length definitions and the string field data is displayed or printed under control of the address pointer and imbedded format control codes.

Bled diffuser fed secondary combustion system for gas turbines
column13: The present subject matter provides a system for modifying static pressure recoveries and emissions formation within a gas turbine. The system includes a bled diffuser positioned downstream from a compressor section of the gas turbine and a bleed duct extending from the bled diffuser. The bleed duct may be configured to direct bleed air from the pressurized airflow exiting the compressor section to a secondary combustion system located downstream from the main combustion system in a combustor. The bleed air flowing into the secondary combustion system may be mixed with fuel to form an air/fuel mixture.

column12: COMBUSTION SYSTEM WITH PANEL FUEL INJECTOR
column13: The present disclosure is directed to an annular combustion system. The annular combustion system includes an inner liner and an outer liner that define there between an annulus that circumscribes a centerline of the combustion system. The annulus includes a plurality of primary combustion zones defined at an upstream end thereof and further defines a plurality of secondary combustion zones downstream of the primary combustion zones. The annular combustion system further includes a plurality of fuel nozzles where at least one fuel nozzle discharges a combustible mixture into a respective primary combustion zone of the plurality of primary combustion zones. A plurality of panel fuel injectors is disposed between adjacent fuel nozzles. The plurality of panel fuel injectors extends in an axially downstream direction so as to separate adjacent primary combustion zones. Each panel fuel injector discharges a combustible mixture into at least one secondary combustion zone.

column12: Sonic transducer mounting
column13: A sonic transducer incorporating a rigid plate-like transmitting member coupled to electromechanical compression wave generating means such as a piezoelectric crystal for transmitting sonic energy in a medium. The transmitting means is damped to prevent ringing, and the transducer is particularly responsive to the high frequency audio spectrum. The sheet-like configuration of the transducer enables it to be recessed within a generally flat panel such as a front panel of a speaker cabinet while nevertheless being separated from the inside of the cabinet to avoid interaction with a conventional cone-type speaker that may be mounted in the same cabinet. The sheet-like transducer is resiliently mounted in a direction contrary to the principal direction of sonic energy propagation in the transducer to minimize loss of sonic energy to supporting structure such as a speaker cabinet.

column12: REPORT GENERATION CONTROL SYSTEM FOR TEXT PROCESSING MACHINES
column13: AT9-81-035 REPORT GENERATION CONTROL SYSTEM FOR TEXT PROCESSING MACHINES A report generation control system for operating a text processor to produce output reports containing inter-report summary data from data processing-type files. The system is compatible with text pagination functions and is useable by a text entry/revision operator with no programming skills. The system permits the operator to describe the desired report by keying an example page of the report in the exact desired format and then editing the example page by replacing the required variable file data examples with descriptive instructions and by inserting summary instructions. The system scans the edited example page for instructions, breaks it down into logical components and compiles the components into program routines which will produce the desired output report.

column12: STAGED FUEL AND AIR INJECTION IN COMBUSTION SYSTEMS OF GAS TURBINES
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide novel systems relating to downstream or axially staged injection of air and fuel in combustion systems of gas turbines.SOLUTION: A gas turbine that includes a working fluid flowpath 37 extending aftward from a forward injector 21 in a combustor 13. The combustor 13 may include an inner radial wall 24, an outer radial wall 25, and a flow annulus therebetween 26. A staged injector 51 may intersect the flow annulus 26 to attain within the working fluid flowpath an injection point by which aftward and forward annulus sections are defined. An air directing structure may include an aftward intake section that corresponds to the aftward annulus section, and a forward intake section that corresponds to the forward annulus section. The air directing structure may be configured to: direct air entering through the aftward intake section through the aftward annulus section in a forward direction to the staged injector 51; and direct air entering through the forward intake section through the forward annulus section in a forward direction to the forward injector 21.SELECTED DRAWING: Figure 5

column12: Method of associating objects on different pages of a notebook window.
column13: Provided is a method and apparatus for aiding a program builder in linking objects (123, 124) in a visual application builder where the objects are on different pages (121, 125) of the application builder notebook. When the target object (124) is on another page (125) of the notebook, the user selects the source object (123). The user then flips the notebook page. During the page flipping, the selected source object is shown as an outline shadow with a page number (P1) under it. If the new page is shown with the desired target object on it, the user drags and drops a link (127) between the shadow source object and the target object to make a connection. If the user flips to the source object page, then the target object will become the shadow object with a page number label next to it. If the shadow object is too big and covers the target object completely or for any other reason, the user may want to optionally use the outside page connector technique. This can be done by dragging and dropping the link from the source object to any point outside the notebook. The ending point of the link (outside the notebook) will have an outside page connector ICON appear. The user flips the notebook to find the target object. After the target object page is displayed, the user draws a link from the outside page connector to the target object. The user may navigate between the source and target pages by clicking on the page connector ICON.

column13: 18,103. Berry, C. H., and Walthew, E. J. Aug. 21. Lubricating the cylinders, pistons, and valves of steam, pneumatic, and like hammers. A ratchetfeed lubricator a is fixed to the frame of the hammer or in any other convenient position. The operating-lever c for the hammer is connected by a link d to the arm e, which carries the pawl for actuating the ratchet-wheel f of the lubricator. By this arrangement, lubricant is fed to the hammer &c. at each operation of the lever c. The pipe v leads from the lubricator to the steam &c. pipe, and is provided with a cock u. The handle t of this cock is connected, by a link s, to one arm of a bell-crank lever h pivoted on the hammer frame. The other arm of the lever h takes between collars on a rod o, which is coupled to the spindle q of the stop valve p. When the rod o is moved to open or close the valve p, the valve u is opened or closed simultaneously.

column12: System and method for producing hydrogen rich fuel
column13: A system for providing hydrogen enriched fuel includes first and second gas turbines 12,14. The second gas turbine 14 receives a fuel from a fuel supply and portion 36 of compressed working fluid from the first gas turbine 12 and produces a reformed fuel, and a fuel skid 20 provides fluid communication between a turbine 54 in the second gas turbine 14 and a combustor 24 in the first gas turbine 12. A method for providing hydrogen enriched fuel includes diverting a portion of a first compressed working fluid from a first compressor to a second compressor and providing a second compressed working fluid from the second compressor. Mixing a first portion of a compressed fuel with the second compressed working fluid in a reformer to produce a reformed fuel, flowing a second portion of the compressed fuel to a second turbine for cooling, and flowing the reformed fuel through the second turbine to cool the reformed fuel.

column12: COMBUSTION SYSTEM WITH PANEL FUEL INJECTOR
column13: The present disclosure is directed to an annular combustion system. The annular combustion system includes an inner liner and an outer liner that define therebetween an annulus that circumscribes a centerline of the combustion system. The annulus includes a plurality of primary combustion zones defined at an upstream end thereof and further defines a plurality of secondary combustion zones downstream of the primary combustion zones. The annular combustion system further includes a plurality of fuel nozzles where at least one fuel nozzle discharges a combustible mixture into a respective primary combustion zone of the plurality of primary combustion zones. A plurality of panel fuel injectors is disposed between adjacent fuel nozzles. The plurality of panel fuel injectors extends in an axially downstream direction so as to separate adjacent primary combustion zones. Each panel fuel injector discharges a combustible mixture into at least one secondary combustion zone.

column12: A seal arrangement
column13: A seal arrangement is for sealing a clearance defined between two components (2 and 4). The seal comprises at least one brush seal element (18) and at least one fin element (20) disposed successively in a sealing direction. The elements (18 and 20) project from the two components (2 and 4) into the clearance (6) between the two components (2 and 4) such that when viewed in the sealing direction the elements (18) and elements (20) overlap. A leakage path through or around either element (18) or element (20) is thereby restricted by the following element producing overall a tortuous leakage path (36) through the seal. The brush seal element may contact the opposed component. The flexability of the brush seal elements eases assembly of the components.

column12: Process for fractionating a mixture of rare earth metals by ion exchange.
column13: A continuous process for partially or completely fractionating a mixture of rare earth metals by ion exchange is disclosed. A leach liquor including rare earth elements is contacted with a cationic exchange resin and the rare earth elements is then contacted with progressively increasing concentrations of an alpha-hydroxy acid having a pH high enough to maintain the acid as a dissociated species but low enough so as not to exceed the solubility products of the rare earths. The various fractions may be subjected to further fractionation steps in one or more additional process levels.

Disc screen separator device
column13: A disc screen separator device for separating or classifying materials. The disc screen separator device includes a plurality of parallel, spaced apart corotating shafts each having a plurality of spaced apart separator discs mounted thereon for rotation therewith. The separator discs on adjacent shafts are interspaced. A plurality of spacers are located between adjacent separator discs on each shaft to maintain the spacing between adjacent separator discs on each shaft. Both the separator discs and spacer discs are fabricated of a resilient material. In an alternative embodiment, a disc screen separator device includes a plurality of sets of first shafts, the shafts of the sets of first shafts being parallel, spaced apart, and corotating with a plurality of spaced apart separator discs mounted on the first shafts for rotation therewith. A second shaft is located in the interval between sets of first shafts with a plurality of agitator discs mounted on the second shafts for rotation therewith. The agitator discs on the second shafts are interspaced with the separator discs on the first shafts of the shaft sets adjacent to the second shaft.

column12: Integrated combustion nozzle having a unified head end
column13: Integrated combustion nozzles and turbomachines are provided. An integrated combustion nozzle includes a unified head end coupled to a combustion liner. The unified head end includes a first fuel nozzle and a second fuel nozzle disposed at a forward end portion of the combustion liner. A fuel plenum is defined between the first fuel nozzle and the second fuel nozzle. A first liner portion extends from the first fuel nozzle and into an opening of a first wall of the combustion liner such that the first liner portion forms a continuous surface with the first wall. The unified head end further includes a second liner portion that extends from the second fuel nozzle and into an opening of a second wall of the combustion liner such that the second liner portion forms a continuous surface with the second wall.

Report generation control system for text processing machines
column13: A report generation control system for operating a text processor to produce output reports containing inter-report summary data from data processing-type files. The system is compatible with text pagination functions and is useable by a text entry/revision operator with no programming skills. The system permits the operator to describe the desired report by keying an example page of the report in the exact desired format and then editing the example page by replacing the required variable file data examples with descriptive instructions and by inserting summary instructions. The system scans the edited example page for instructions, breaks it down into logical components and compiles the components into program routines which will produce the desired output report.

column12: Thin aspect lighting system with cutoff

The system and method include at least one module having a reflector that is generally elliptical in one cross-section and generally parabolic in another cross-section. Each module is adapted to generate at least one of a flat beam pattern, a high beam pattern or a low beam pattern, such as a low beam pattern with a kink or elbow. Also shown is a headlamp assembly having a plurality of modules that generate the same or a different light beam pattern. Manipulation and variation of facets or positions of various components, such as at least one light source provides improved characteristics in one or more of the light beam patterns.

column12: Device for producing laser radiation at a variable or selectable wavelength
column13: A device permitting a single primary laser producing a collimated beam at a given wavelength, to be used for different purposes by converting the collimated beam to a beam of different wavelength. The device comprises a secondary laser disposed within a body removably attached to the distal end of an articulated arm delivery system attached to the primary laser. Preferably, the secondary laser is interchangeable with respect to the delivery system thus to extend the wavelength (color) coverage of the primary laser according to the required wavelength conversion. The secondary laser may include an optical crystal or a circulated organic dye solution within a removable cell or reservoir. Appropriate lenses are provided to focus the primary beam and to determine the spot diameter of the conversed beam.

column12: Capacitive boost circuit for extending hold up time
column13: A circuit for extending the operation of an electrical load after interruption of its power source. The circuit includes bulk capacitors charged by the power source and regulated to a predetermined voltage near their peak-voltage rating. The bulk capacitors are isolated from the power source capacitors during normal power source operation. When the power source is interrupted, the bulk capacitors are used to hold-up the load. The circuit obtains maximum hold-up time for a given physical bulk capacitor size, while also providing a consistent hold-up time over a range of power source voltages.

column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide novel systems related to the downstream or axially staged injection of air and fuel in combustion systems of gas turbines.SOLUTION: A gas turbine includes a working fluid flowpath 37 extending aftward from a forward injector 21 in a combustor 13. The combustor 13 includes an inner radial wall 24, an outer radial wall 25, and a flow annulus 26 therebetween. The air directing structure is configured to: direct air entering through the aftward intake section through the aftward annulus section in a forward direction to the staged injector 51; and direct air entering through the forward intake section through the forward annulus section in an aftward direction to the staged injector 51.SELECTED DRAWING: Figure 5

column13: Refinery or similar streams containing NH.sub.3 are processed in a sulfur plant having separate burners for the NH.sub.3 -containing acid gas stream and for the NH.sub.3 -free acid gas stream. A sampling device is provided for continuously or periodically sampling the combustion products from the unit burning the NH.sub.3 -containing gas. The H.sub.2 S/SO.sub.2 ratios at this sample point and in the sulfur plant tail gas are used to control the operation of the system.
