INTEGRATED COMBUSTION NOZZLE HAVING UNIFIED HEAD END
column13: To provide an integrated combustion nozzle.SOLUTION: Integrated combustion nozzles (100) and turbomachines (10) are provided. The integrated combustion nozzle (100) includes a unified head end (200) coupled to a combustion liner (110). The unified head end (200) includes a first fuel nozzle (202) and a second fuel nozzle (204) disposed at a forward end portion of the combustion liner (110). A fuel plenum (248) is defined between the first fuel nozzle (202) and the second fuel nozzle (204). A first liner portion (206) extends from the first fuel nozzle (202) and into openings (170, 172) of a first wall of the combustion liner (110) so that the first liner portion (206) forms a continuous surface with the first wall. The unified head end (200) further includes a second liner portion (208) that extends from the second fuel nozzle (204) and into openings (170, 172) of a second wall of the combustion liner (110) so that the second liner portion (208) forms a continuous surface with the second wall.SELECTED DRAWING: Figure 3

column12: Improvements in or relating to linings for use with centrifugal blasting wheels
column13: 1,037,811. Blasting. TILGHMAN'S Ltd. June 17, 1964 [March 18, 1963], No. 6396/63 Heading B3D. A lining for the guard housing of a centrifugal blasting wheel comprises a plurality of lining pieces, made of blast wear-resisting material and provided with mating members adjacent their edges so that the pieces fit together to provide an assembled lining whose joints are proof against leakage of abrasive shot and whose inner surface has contours which are substantially non-angular. A housing 12 for a centrifugal blasting wheel has a lining of wear-resistant material. Each vertical side of the lining is made up of segmental piece 13, 14, 15 held by bolts 16 to the inside of the housing. The sides are bridged by pieces 18, 19, 21, 22, 23. The pieces 18, 19 abut lateral projections 20 formed on the sides of the lining. The pieces 21, 22, 23 are of channel cross-section and have lateral projections allowing them to rest on the top edges of the side lining pieces 14. The upper ends of the pieces 18, 19 are flared at 25; the piece 22 is flared at both ends. Adjusting screws 26 in the housing 12 bear on the pieces 18, 19. The housing has a lid 27 provided with a rubber plug 28 which bears on the piece 22 when screws 29 are tightened.

column12: Reheat method for use in sulfur recovery process
column13: The problem of bypass reheating in split flow plants with less than about 20 mol percent hydrogen sulfide in the feed is overcome by diverting at least a portion of the bypass gas stream and mixing it with the furnace effluent. The resulting mixture, after passing through a heat exchanger, is adjusted to the proper first reactor inlet temperature.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS IN OR RELATING TO HORIZON SIGHTING SENSORS
column13: 1280441 Horizon detector BARR & STROUD Ltd 29 Dec 1970 [6 Jan 1970] 695/70 Heading H4D [Also in Division G2] A horizon sensor comprises a double-sided mirror 11 oscillated about a horizontal axis 13 and a detector 12, an infra-red image received through lens 10 being scanned by mirror 11 and detector 12. The signal from the detector 12 is fed to a light source 14 which is energized when the discontinuity between the infra-red received from the sea and the sky is detected. The light from source 14, which may be a point source, is reflected from mirror 11 and through a lens 15 astigmatizing lens 16 to give a line image of the horizin. The sensor of Fig. 1 may be incorporated into a sectant to provide a horizon image in darkness. The mirror 11 may be one-sided, the light from source 14 being reflected from the same side of the mirror as the received infra-red radiation, a prism then being included between mirror 11 and lens 15 so that the resultant light is parallel to the radiation incident on lens 10. The mirror 11 may be replaced by a rotated multi-sided prism. In order that the horizon line image may be horizontal irrespective of the orientation of the sensor the lenses 15 and 16 may be pendulously mounted. The lens 16 may be dispensed with, a pendulously mounted diaphragm having spaced parallel slits then being provided at source 14, or a pendulously mounted strip light being used as source 14. The source 14 may be continuously energized, the detector 12 then controlling a shuttering arrangement. To correct for any time delay between detection of the horizon discontinuity and operation of the source 14 two light sources may be used to produce images above and below the true horizon, or the sensor may be arranged to produce these two images from one light source. A pendulously mounted graticule may be associated with the light source to provide the horizon line.

column12: REPORT GENERATION CONTROL SYSTEM FOR TEXT PROCESSING MACHINES
column13: A report generation control system for operating a text processor to produce output reports containing inter-report summary data from data processing-type files. The system is compatible with text pagination functions and is useable by a text entry/revision operator with no programming skills. The system permits the operator to describe the desired report by keying an example page of the report in the exact desired format and then editing the example page by replacing the required variable file data examples with descriptive instructions such as (FRP) (DCG) (RCD) and by inserting summary instructions such as (CGS) (FRS). The system scans the edited example page for instructions, breaks it down into logical components and compiles the components into program routines which will produce the desired output renort.

column13: The invention relates to a multi-tube late lean injector. The micromixer injector includes a fuel plenum to receive a supply of fuel. A plurality of premixing tubes extend through the fuel plenum. Each tube has a plurality of fuel holes formed therein to receive the supply of fuel for mixing with air in the tube. The micromixer has a tapering profile such that an overall inlet area of the plurality of premixing tubes on an upstream face of the micromixer is larger than an overall outlet area of the plurality of premixing tubes on a downstream face such that the plurality of premixing tubes are relatively spaced-apart at the upstream face and more densely packed at the downstream face. Additionally, an air inlet of each tube has a first geometrical shape and the outlet of each tube has a second geometrical shape that is different from the first geometrical shape.

RADIATION SCANNING SYSTEM WITH TWO RELATIVELY MOVABLE REFLECTORS
column13: Apparatus for use in a radiation scanning system comprising a radiation detector and an optical system arranged to scan radiation from a field of view across the radiation detector. The optical system includes two sets of planar reflective surfaces, one set being movable relative to the other, and a rotary assembly carrying one of the sets and rotatable about an axis of rotation. The detector is arranged relative to the optical system such that the radiation enters the detector after sequential reflection from reflective surfaces of the two sets, and the surfaces which effect the sequential reflection being separated by a predetermined amount and being located with respect to the axis of rotation such that the angle of incidence of radiation at the detector is independent of the position of the radiation in the field of view.

column12: Improvements in or relating to electric circuits
column13: 1,001,041. Transistor amplitude-discriminating circuits; pilot-controlled A.V.C. GENERAL ELECTRIC CO. Ltd. Oct. 23, 1963 [Nov. 1, 1962], No. 41377/62. Headings H3T and H4R. A circuit for producing a predetermined response when the voltage level of an input signal (e.g. a pilot signal in a communication system) falls outside defined limits, comprises two bi-stable trigger circuits one of which changes state when the input signal voltage increases positively to exceed a first voltage level but which does not return to its initial state until the input signal has fallen below a level less positive than the first voltage level and the other of which changes state when the input signal voltage increases negatively to exceed a second voltage level but which does not return to its initial state until the input signal has fallen below a level less negative than the second voltage level. Thus both trigger circuits remain in their initial states so long as the input signal voltage remains within the limits defined by the first and second voltage levels; however, once a circuit has changed state its state is not restored until the input signal voltage has returned to within limits narrower than those defined by the first and second voltage levels. The circuit may form part of terminal receiving equipment in which a pilot signal transmitted with the intelligence signal is used to effect gain control, the circuit serving to indicate when excessive changes on the pilot-signal amplitude, such as would be due to a fault, have taken place. The two bi-stable circuits 43, 44 comprise Schmitt-trigger circuits constituted by transistors 2, 6 and 13, 16 respectively and so biased that for input-signals levels within the defined limits, transistors 6 and 13 are conducting. The circuit 44 includes an inverting output transistor 24, so that for normal levels of input signal, the output transistors 6 and 24 of the circuits 43, 44 are both conducting. The outputs from the two trigger circuits are applied via diode gates 11, 28 to emitter-follower transistor 29; thus for normal input-signal levels both transistors 31 and 36 are conducting and relay 39 is energized. Reversal of the state of either of the bi-stable circuits results in a considerably more negative voltage being established at the base of emitter follower 29, this switching transistors 31 and 36 and so releasing relay 39 to cause an alarm to be operated and/or some other control to be effected. Transistor 22 forms part of the load for transistor 13 and serves to delay the onset of bottoming in that transistor.

Improvements in or relating to waveguides
column13: 960,683. Electromagnetic waveguides. MARCONI CO. Ltd. June 14, 1960 [Nov. 30, 1959], No. 40577/59. Heading H1W. A waveguide coupling arrangement comprises two hollow circular sectioned waveguides 1 and 2 joined end to end and constructed to propagate therethrough radio energy in the H on mode, the waveguide walls providing conductive paths parallel to the axes of the guides and each sharing a different impedance over the major part of its length, at least one of the guides, 1, having internal grooves la whose dimensions are varied in such manner that the minimum diameter of the guide over the grooved portion remains constant, thereby to provide a gradual transition of surface impedance from the value over the major part of the lengths of the guide to another value approaching that of the surface impedance of the other guides at the end thereof. The guides 1 and 2 are held together by a sleeve 4, the guide 2 in Fig. 1 being a helical guide 2a in a sheath 2b of synthetic material. In the construction shown in Figs. 1 and 3 the grooving la is in the form of internal ring triangular grooves, in a solid walled grade, which are of a depth and/or width which is increased from groove to groove towards the end of the guide or of a depth and/or width which is increased from group of grooves to group of grooves towards the end of the guide. Alternatively the grooving can be in the form of a screw thread of increasing depth and/or width towards the end of the guide. In the construction shown in Fig. 2 the guide 2 consists of a metal helix 2c whose turns are in contact contained in a sheath 2b of synthetic material, the metal helix being formed of metal wire or strip the cross-sectional dimensions of which are reduced, either gradually or in steps, over a length at one end of the guide. In the construction shown in Fig. 3 the flexible guide 2 is built up of metal rings 2d spaced by rings 2e of dielectric material. The desired gradual variation of surface impedance, which may be effected in a solid walled guide or a flexible guide, or in both, can be in accordance with a linear, binormal or exponential law.

column13: A gas turbine that includes a working fluid flowpath extending aftward from a forward injector in a combustor. The combustor may include an inner radial wall, an outer radial wall, and, therebetween, a flow annulus. A staged injector may intersect the flow annulus so to attain an injection point within the working fluid flowpath by which aftward and forward annulus sections are defined. Air directing structure may include an aftward intake section that corresponds to the aftward annulus section and a forward intake section that corresponds to the forward annulus section. The air directing structure may be configured to: direct air entering through the aftward intake section through the aftward annulus section in a forward direction to the staged injector; and direct air entering through the forward intake section through the forward annulus section in an aftward direction to the staged injector.

column12: Gasturbine mit einem System zur Erhöhung der statischen Druckerholung stromabwärts von einem Verdichterabschnitt der Gasturbine und zur Reduzierung der Emissionserzeugung der Gasturbine.
column13: Der vorliegende Gegenstand ergibt eine Gasturbine mit einem System zur Erhöhung der statischen Druckerholung stromabwärts von einem Verdichterabschnitt (14) der Gasturbine und zur Reduzierung der Emissionserzeugung der Gasturbine. Das System enthält einen Anzapfdiffusor (52), der stromabwärts von dem Verdichterabschnitt (14) einer Gasturbine positioniert ist, und einen Zapfkanal (54), der sich von dem Anzapfdiffusor (52) aus erstreckt. Der Zapfkanal (54) ist konfiguriert, um von dem Anzapfdiffusor (52) abgezapfte Luft zu einem sekundären Verbrennungssystem (58) zu führen. Die in das sekundäre Verbrennungssystem (58) einströmende Luft wird mit Brennstoff vermischt, um ein Luft/Brennstoff-Gemisch zu bilden.

column12: ENHANCED LINK 16 DETECTION WITH INTERFERENCE MITIGATION
column13: A method for implementing interference mitigation in wireless network such as a Link (16) network does not require interference recognition and does not degrade signal detection even in the absence of interference. An unmitigated correlation score is obtained by correlating received, unmitigated preamble symbols with expected symbols. At least one of the input signals is also correlated after mitigation to obtain a mitigated signal. A mitigated correlation sore is obtained from the mitigated signals, and a mixed correlation score is obtained by combining mitigated and unmitigated signals. A signal is detected if any of the correlation scores exceeds a corresponding threshold. Embodiments use the unmitigated correlation for subsequent message time of arrival determination if the unmitigated correlation score is above its detection threshold. In embodiments, mitigation is applied to only one of the message frequencies. Implementation of the disclosed method does not require excessive additional electronic resources.

The second feedback path may also, through a further detector, bias conductively the modulator transistor acting as a switching impedance for the unidirectional modulation input to the oscillator. The output may be rectified so that the circuit is a D.C. amplifier.

column12: Multi-tooth drill with improved chisel edge
column13: A three-flute, three-tooth drill has a central peak on the central axis between three V-shaped teeth that provides improved cutting chisel edges. The rake faces, which produce the V-shaped cutting teeth, are setback of radial planes of the drill, and have a slight positive rake angle. Gashes are ground into the clearance faces in such a way as to produce the peak with three chisel edges, each of which curves radially out and merges into a straight cutting edge with no reversal in slope. Therefore, the chisel edges cut cleanly, due both to their positive axial rake, and due to the fact that there are no undercuts along their length in which chips could build up.

column12: System and method for producing hydrogen rich fuel
column13: The invention relates to a system and a method for producing hydrogen rich fuel. More specifically, a system for providing hydrogen rich fuel includes first and second gas turbines. The second gas turbine receives a fuel from a fuel supply and portion of compressed working fluid from the first gas turbine and produces a reformed fuel, and a fuel skid provides fluid communication between a turbine in the second gas turbine and a combustor in the first gas turbine. A method for providing hydrogen rich fuel includes diverting a portion of a first compressed working fluid from a first compressor to a second compressor and providing a second compressed working fluid from the second compressor. A first portion of a compressed fuel and the second compressed working fluid are mixed in a reformer to produce a reformed fuel, and a second portion of the compressed fuel is enabled to flow to a second turbine for cooling, and the reformed fuel is enabled to flow through the second turbine to cool the reformed fuel.

column12: Staged fuel and air injection in combustion systems of gas turbines
column13: A gas turbine including a working fluid flowpath extending aftward from a forward injector in a combustor. The combustor may include an inner radial wall, an outer radial wall, and, therebetween, a flow annulus, and a third radial wall formed about the outer radial wall that forms an outer flow annulus. A staged injector may intersect the flow annulus so to attain an injection point within the working fluid flowpath by which aftward and forward annulus sections are defined. Air directing structure may include an aftward intake section corresponding to the aftward annulus section and a forward intake section corresponding to the forward annulus section. The air directing structure may include a switchback coolant flowpath to direct air from the compressor discharge cavity to the staged injector. The switchback coolant flowpath may include an upstream section through the flow annulus, and a downstream section through the outer flow annulus.

column12: Impingement panel for a turbomachine
column13: An integrated combustor nozzle includes a combustion liner that extends radially between an inner liner segment and an outer liner segment. The combustion liner includes a forward end portion, an aft end portion, a first side wall, and a second side wall. The aft end portion of the combustion liner defines a turbine nozzle. The integrated combustor nozzle further includes an impingement panel having an impingement plate disposed along an exterior surface of one of the inner liner segment or the outer liner segment. The impingement plate defines a plurality of impingement holes that direct coolant in discrete jets towards the exterior surface of the inner liner segment or the outer liner segment. The impingement panel is radially spaced from the exterior surface to form a cooling flow gap therebetween. The impingement panel includes a collection duct that extends from the impingement panel and defines a collection passage.

column12: System und Verfahren zum Produzieren wasserstoffreichen Brennstoffes
column13: Ein System (10) zum Bereitstellen von mit Wasserstoff angereichertem Brennstoff schließt erste und zweite Gasturbinen (12, 14) ein. Die zweite Gasturbine (14) empfängt einen Teil (34) eines komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (30) von der ersten Gasturbine (12) und produziert einen reformierten Brennstoff (42), und eine Brennstoffschiene (20) stellt eine Strömungsverbindung zwischen einer Turbine (44) in der zweiten Gasturbine (14) und einem Brenner (24) in der ersten Gasturbine (12) bereit. Ein Verfahren zum Bereitstellen von mit Wasserstoff angereichertem Brennstoff schließt das Ableiten eines Teiles (34) eines ersten komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (30) von einem ersten Verdichter (22) zu einem zweiten Verdichter (36) und das Bereitstellen eines zweiten komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (38) durch den zweiten Verdichter (36) ein. Das Verfahren schließt weiter das Vermischen eines Brennstoffes (18) mit dem zweiten komprimierten Arbeitsfluid (38) in einem Reformer (40), um einen reformierten Brennstoff (42) zu produzieren, das Leiten des reformierten Brennstoffes (42) durch eine zweite Turbine (44), um den reformierten Brennstoff (42) zu kühlen, und das Verbinden der zweiten Turbine (44) mit dem zweiten Verdichter (36) ein, sodass die zweite Turbine (44) den zweiten Verdichter (36) antreibt.

PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To prevent an internal loss caused by absorption between valence bands and decrease of carrier mobility in an active area caused by a laser and an impurity diffusion in an amplifier concerning the pollution in an active area although a photoelectron semiconductor device using a p-i-n double hetero structure, as its default, diffuses a p type impurity for a second clad layer in an active layer and a distinction which obviously demarcated between a doped process clad layer and the active area intending an undoped process is tend not to exist.

SOLUTION: A semiconductor structure includes a p-i-n double hetero structure, and a high dissoluble layer is provided in the p-i-n double hetero structure to decrease diffusion of the p type impurity from the clad layer to the active layer. column12: Micro-Channel Cooling of Integrated Combustor Nozzle of a Segmented Annular Combustion System
column13: A segmented annular combustion system includes integrated combustor nozzles, each of which has a fuel injection panel disposed radially between an inner liner segment and an outer liner segment. The fuel injection panel includes an aft end portion, a first side wall, a second side wall, premixing channels defined between the first side wall and the side wall, and injection outlets defined along at least one of the first side wall and the second side wall. The aft end portion defines a turbine nozzle portion. An interior portion between the first side wall and the second side wall includes walls that extend between the first and second side walls, thereby partitioning the interior portion into discrete air cavities. The liner segments may be cooled by micro-channel cooling passages, which may be fluidly coupled to a collection trough.

column12: System and method for producing hydrogen rich fuel
column13: The invention relates to a system and a method for producing hydrogen rich fuel. A system (10) for providing hydrogen enriched fuel includes first and second gas turbines (12, 14). The second gas turbine (14) receives a portion (34) of compressed working fluid (30) from the first gas turbine (12) and produces a reformed fuel (42), and a fuel skid (20) provides fluid communication between a turbine (44) in the second gas turbine (14) and a combustor (24) in the first gas turbine (12). A method for providing hydrogen enriched fuel includes diverting a portion (34) of a first compressed working fluid (30) from a first compressor (22) to a second compressor (36) and providing a second compressed working fluid (38) from the second compressor (36). The method further includes mixing a fuel (18) with the second compressed working fluid (38) in a reformer (40) to produce a reformed fuel (42), flowing the reformed fuel (42) through a second turbine (44) to cool the reformed fuel (42), and connecting the second turbine (44) to the second compressor (36) so that the second turbine (44) drives the second compressor (36).

Metal strip shearing and coiling
column13: Apparatus for coiling successive lengths of metal strip onto mandrels 7,8, comprising means for changing the strip path from a path leading to the mandrel 8 currently being wound to a path to a new mandrel when the current strip ends and a new strip appears. The new mandrel has mandrel strip guide means 12 comprising a chain of driven mandrel guide rollers located around the new mandrel in its initial position to receive the leading edge of a new length of strip and guide it around the mandrel. Adjacent rollers in the chain have interlocking grooves and flanges. Similar chains of rollers 3, 5, and 13 are used to guide the strip between the shears 2 and the mandrels. The new mandrel 7 is positioned in an initial position such that the strip path to it is a straight path, and the mandrels are mounted on a carousel 6 which moves that mandrel to a second position such that the strip path to it is an angled path 14 the first segment of which is common with the first part of the straight strip path. A tail restraining unit 11 holds the tail of the old strip onto its mandrel.

Operation and Turndown of a Segmented Annular Combustion System
column13: The present disclosure is directed to the operation and turndown of a segmented annular combustion system. The method includes injecting, via a fuel nozzle, a combustible mixture into a primary combustion zone between an adjacent pair of integrated combustor nozzles and burning the combustible mixture. The method further includes flowing air and injecting fuel into a premixing channel defined within a first integrated combustor nozzle to produce a second combustible mixture. The second combustible mixture is injected into a secondary combustion zone where it is combusted. The flow of combustion gases is accelerated, via turbine nozzles of the integrated combustor nozzles, toward turbine blades of a downstream turbine section. column12: SEMICONDUCTOR DEVICE HAVING CURRENT CONFINEMENT STRUCTURE
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a semiconductor device which produces a rapid processing band and good life characteristics. SOLUTION: The semiconductor device comprises a doped semiconductor substrate (2) of a first conductivity, a buried hetero-junction active layer (10) above the substrate, a current conduction region (4) above the active layer, and one or more current confinement regions (20) formed on the substrate adjacent to the active layer, with the current conduction region and the current confinement region being arranged in use to channel electric current to the active layer. Each current confinement region includes (a) a diode junction current blocking structure which comprises a first blocking layer (18) and a second blocking layer (17) formed between the first blocking layer and the substrate, with the first and second blocking layers forming a reverse-biased diode junction to block a current via the current confinement region, and (b) a graded second blocking layer (7) in contact with the second blocking layer (17). The graded second current blocking layer (7) has a dopant concentration that falls from the second current blocking layer (17) toward the substrate.

column12: Combustion system with panel fuel injector
column13: The present disclosure is directed to an annular combustion system. The annular combustion system includes an inner liner and an outer liner that define therebetween an annulus that circumscribes a centerline of the combustion system. The annulus includes a plurality of primary combustion zones defined at an upstream end thereof and further defines a plurality of secondary combustion zones downstream of the primary combustion zones. The annular combustion system further includes a plurality of fuel nozzles where at least one fuel nozzle discharges a combustible mixture into a respective primary combustion zone of the plurality of primary combustion zones. A plurality of panel fuel injectors is disposed between adjacent fuel nozzles. The plurality of panel fuel injectors extends in an axially downstream direction so as to separate adjacent primary combustion zones. Each panel fuel injector discharges a combustible mixture into at least one secondary combustion zone.

Operation and turndown of a segmented annular combustion system
column13: The present disclosure is directed to the operation and turndown of a segmented annular combustion system. The method includes injecting, via a fuel nozzle, a combustible mixture into a primary combustion zone between an adjacent pair of integrated combustor nozzles and burning the combustible mixture. The method further includes flowing air and injecting fuel into a premixing channel defined within a first integrated combustor nozzle to produce a second combustible mixture. The second combustible mixture is injected into a secondary combustion zone where it is combusted. The flow of combustion gases is accelerated, via turbine nozzles of the integrated combustor nozzles, toward turbine blades of a downstream turbine section. The method permits turndown of the combustion system by reducing or shutting off fuel to various components of the combustion system.

column12: 패널 연료 분사기를 갖는 연소 시스템
column13: 본 개시내용은 환형 연소 시스템에 관한 것이다. 환형 연소 시스템은 연소 시스템의 중심선의 둘레를 에워싸는 고리를 그 사이에 형성하는 내부 라이너 및 외부 라이너를 포함한다. 고리는 그 상류측 단부에 형성된 복수의 1차 연소 구역을 포함하고, 1차 연소 구역의 하류측에 복수의 2차 연소 구역을 또한 형성한다. 환형 연소 시스템은 복수의 연료 노즐을 더 포함하고, 여기서 적어도 하나의 연료 노즐은 복수의 1차 연소 구역의 각각의 1차 연소 구역 내로 연소성 혼합물을 토출한다. 복수의 패널 연료 분사기가 인접한 연료 노즐 사이에 배치된다. 복수의 패널 연료 분사기는 인접한 1차 연소 구역을 분리하기 위해 축방향 하류측 방향으로 연장된다. 각각의 패널 분사기는 연소성 혼합물을 적어도 하나의 2차 연소 구역 내로 토출한다.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR PRODUCING HYDROGEN RICH FUEL
column13: A system for providing hydrogen enriched fuel includes first and second gas turbines. The second gas turbine receives a portion of compressed working fluid from the first gas turbine and produces a reformed fuel, and a fuel skid provides fluid communication between a turbine in the second gas turbine and a combustor in the first gas turbine. A method for providing hydrogen enriched fuel includes diverting a portion of a first compressed working fluid from a first compressor to a second compressor and providing a second compressed working fluid from the second compressor. The method further includes mixing a fuel with the second compressed working fluid in a reformer to produce a reformed fuel, flowing the reformed fuel through a second turbine to cool the reformed fuel, and connecting the second turbine to the second compressor so that the second turbine drives the second compressor.

column12: A METHOD OF CARRYING-OUT A RADIO PROPAGATION SURVEY
A method of carrying out a radio propagation survey
column13: A method of carrying out a radio propagation survey in which a site (10) FIG 1 which may be an industrial site, such as a power station, or an urban area, is divided into a plurality of elemental areas (12) of a size greater than twenty times the wavelength of the carrier frequency of a test signal transmitted by a base station (14). An operator equipped with a receiver (18) having a communications probability indicator (22) (Figures 2 and 3 (not shown)) proceeds from one elemental area to the next, either on foot or in a vehicle, monitoring a particular characteristic of the transmitted signal and the number of occurrences of that characteristic within a predetermined sampling period in each elemental area, thereby determining the quality of reception of that characteristic. This characteristic may be either the carrier strength or SINAD (the ratio of the [signal plus noise plus distortion] to [noise plus distortion]). In order to conduct a survey for two-way radio communication the power output of the base station is adjusted to equal that of the weakest transmitter to be used in the radio system. <IMAGE>

column12: Method of connecting objects on different notebook pages
column13: A visual procedure aides the program builder in linking objects in a visual application builder where the objects are on different pages of the application builder notebook. When the target object is on another page of the notebook, the user selects the source object. The user then flips the notebook page. During the page flipping, the selected source object is shown as an outline shadow with a page number under it. If the new page is shown with the desired target object on it, the user drags and drops a link between the shadow source object and the target object to make a connection. If the user flips to the source object page, then the target object will become the shadow object with a page number label next to it. If the shadow object is too big and covers the target object completely or for any other reason, the user may want to optionally use the outside page connector technique. This can be done by dragging and dropping the link from the source object to any point outside the notebook. The ending point of the link (outside the notebook) will have an outside page connector ICON appear. The user flips the notebook to find the target object. After the target object page is displayed, the user draws a link from the outside page connector to the target object. The user may navigate between the source and target pages by clicking on the page connector ICON.

column12: Staged fuel and air injection in combustion systems of gas turbine
column13: The invention relates to staged fuel and air injection in combustion systems of a gas turbine, and specifically to a gas turbine including a working fluid flowpath extending aftward from a forward injector in a combustor. The combustor may include an inner radial wall, an outer radial wall, and, therebetween, a flow annulus, and a third radial wall formed about the outer radial wall that forms an outer flow annulus. A staged injector may intersect the flow annulus so to attain an injection point within the working fluid flowpath by which aftward and forward annulus sections are defined. Air directing structure may include an aftward intake section corresponding to the aftward annulus section and a forward intake section corresponding to the forward annulus section. The air directing structure may include a switchback coolant flowpath to direct air from the compressor discharge cavity to the staged injector. The switchback coolant flowpath may include an upstream section through the flow annulus, and a downstream section through the outer flow annulus.

column12: METHOD FOR INTEGRATING STRUCTURED DATA AND STRING DATA ON A TEXT PROCESSING SYSTEM
column13: A METHOD FOR INTEGRATING STRUCTURED DATA AND STRING DATA ON A TEXT PROCESSING SYSTEM An improved method is disclosed for operating an interactive text processing system to integrate and process data having type structured fields of fixed length and data having variable length field text or string field data which contain both graphic data characters and format control characters in the same record. The method involves displaying to the text processing system operator a menu of data type codes selectable through a keyboard for defining the types of data fields in a record. In response to operator selected field types, structured fields of fixed length and address pointers of fixed length for the string fields are established for the records. When the data is keyed in, the structured fields are concatenated with the string field address pointers and the text data, including format control codes, is stored at a system selected address on an auxiliary storage device such as a disk file. The structured field data is displayed or printed under control of the field length definintions and the string field data is displayed or printed under control of the address pointer and imbedded format control codes. column13: The present disclosure is directed to an annular combustion system. The annular combustion system includes an inner liner and an outer liner that define there between an annulus that circumscribes a centerline of the combustion system. The annulus includes a plurality of primary combustion zones defined at an upstream end thereof and further defines a plurality of secondary combustion zones downstream of the primary combustion zones. The annular combustion system further includes a plurality of fuel nozzles where at least one fuel nozzle discharges a combustible mixture into a respective primary combustion zone of the plurality of primary combustion zones. A plurality of panel fuel injectors is disposed between adjacent fuel nozzles. The plurality of panel fuel injectors extends in an axially downstream direction so as to separate adjacent primary combustion zones. Each panel fuel injector discharges a combustible mixture into at least one secondary combustion zone.

column12: ELECTRICAL PICKUP LOCATED IN MOUTHPIECE OF MUSICAL INSTRUMENT UTILIZING PIEZAELECTRIC TRANSDUCER
System und Verfahren zum Produzieren wasserstoffreichen Brennstoffes.
column13: Ein System (10) zum Bereitstellen von mit Wasserstoff angereichertem Brennstoff schliesst erste und zweite Gasturbinen (12, 14) ein. Die zweite Gasturbine (14) empfängt einen Teil (34) eines komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (30) von der ersten Gasturbine (12) und produziert einen reformierten Brennstoff (42), und eine Brennstoffschiene (20) stellt eine Strömungsverbindung zwischen einer Turbine (44) in der zweiten Gasturbine (14) und einem Brenner (24) in der ersten Gasturbine (12) bereit. Ein Verfahren zum Bereitstellen von mit Wasserstoff angereichertem Brennstoff schliesst das Ableiten eines Teiles (34) eines ersten komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (30) von einem ersten Verdichter (22) zu einem zweiten Verdichter (36) und das Bereitstellen eines zweiten komprimierten Arbeitsfluids (38) durch den zweiten Verdichter (36) ein. Das Verfahren schliesst weiter das Vermischen eines Brennstoffes (18) mit dem zweiten komprimierten Arbeitsfluid (38) in einem Reformer (40), um einen reformierten Brennstoff (42) zu produzieren, das Leiten des reformierten Brennstoffes (42) durch eine zweite Turbine (44), um den reformierten Brennstoff (42) zu kühlen, und das Verbinden der zweiten Turbine (44) mit dem zweiten Verdichter (36) ein, sodass die zweite Turbine (44) den zweiten Verdichter (36) antreibt. Das Verfahren umfasst ferner das Leiten des gekühlten reformierten Brennstoffes (42) zu einem Brenner (24).

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR SEPARATING COMPETING ANIONS FROM PER- AND POLYFLUOROALKYL SUBSTANCES (PFAS) IN WATER
column13: A system for separating competing anions from per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) in a flow of water contaminated with PFAS and elevated levels of competing anions that includes a separation subsystem which receives the flow of water contaminated with PFAS and elevated levels of competing anions and separates competing anions from the PFAS and concentrates the PFAS to produce a treated flow of water having separated competing anions therein and a flow of water having a majority of PFAS therein. At least one anion exchange vessel having an anion exchange resin therein receives the flow of water having a majority of PFAS therein and removes PFAS from the water to produce a flow of treated water having a majority of the PFAS removed. column12: Resin impregnated fibrous sheets
column13: 1,146,432. Laminates and laminating. DUNLOP CO. Ltd. 17 June, 1966 [20 July, 1965], No. 30730/65. Heading B5N. [Also in Divisions B2 and C3] A fibrous web of sheet material such as paper or a textile fibre, which may be in the form of a woven fabric or a non-woven fabric may be impregnated with a material comprising the reaction product of (a) a polymer of one or more episulphides having at least two reactive terminal groups and (b) a potentially thermosetting aminoplast by spraying, brushing, spreading and especially dipping techniques and composite laminate structures may subsequently be formed and if desired a layer of a non-fibrous material such as a strip of aluminium or other heat-resistant material may be included to confer heat-resistant properties on the impregnated fibrous material. The fibrous layers may be united together before the impregnating material is applied or they may be non-united layers which are united by the impregnating material itself giving a flexible composite fabric. Layers of fibrous web may be mechanically locked together, for example, by needling, or they may be impregnated and laminated together by means of conventional laminating resins, for example, aminoplastics or phenolin resins and the top web is then impregnated with the impregnating material giving a laminate, which is not usually flexible, having a working surface very resistant to alkali and to chipping. Drying of the impregnated fibrous web is effected at room temperature or at 70-80 C. and curing may be effected at 140-200 C. while the coated web is compressed between press platens. The examples describe the formation of laminates whereby both surfaces of a decorative paper web are coated with the impregnating material and also both surfaces of a white overlay paper web are similarly coated and the two coated webs air-dried, superimposed and pressed together for 10 minutes at 180 C. between chromium plates previously coated with a silicone release agent. The resulting sheet materials may be provided with a backing of adhesive, which may be covered with a release paper. The cured surfaces are resistant to staining by household liquids and cleaners. Uses:-Covering materials for kitchen shelves, walls and tables.

column12: LOW ELECTROMAGNETIC EMISSIONS AND IMPROVED SIGNAL QUALITY VIDEO DRIVE ARCHITECTURE FOR LASER PRINTERS
column13: An electrophotographic image forming apparatus transfers image information relating to an image to be formed on a medium, while mainteining desired low levels of electromagnetic emissions. The apparatus includes an image processor (4) that generates low frequency image information signals containing the image information. Low-frequency interface means (8) are connected to the image processor (4) for transferring the low frequency image information signals. A control circuit (10), connected to the low-frequency interface means (8), receives the low frequency image information signals generated by the image processor (4). The control circuit (10) operates on the low-frequency image information signals to form a high frequency image information signal therefrom, where the high frequency image information signal contains the image information. The apparatus also includes high frequency interface means (12) connected to the printhead control circuit (10) for transferring the high frequency image information signal. An image formation device (16), connected to the high-frequency interface means, forms an image on the medium. The image formation device (16) forms the image based on the image information contained within the high frequency image information signal.

column12: Conjugado de polissacarìdeo, produto, e, processo de ligação de marcação de uma entidade à celulose
column13: "CONJUGADO DE POLISSACARìDEO, PRODUTO, E, PROCESSO DE LIGAçãO DE MARCAçãO DE UMA ENTIDADE à CELULOSE" Um conjugado de polissacarídeo compõe-se de um polissacarídeo com uma entidade ligada tendo um peso molecular de pelo menos 5000, cujo conjugado polissacarídeo sendo capaz de ligar-se à celulose. Os polissacarídeos preferidos incluem xiloglicana de semente de tamarindo, goma de alfarroba, e guar modificado por enzima. A entidade ligada é adequadamente uma proteína tais como uma enzima, anticorpo ou fragmento de anticorpo, ou uma partícula possivelmente tendo um agente de benefício tal como uma fragrância associada com ela. Porque o conjugado polissacarídeo se liga à celulose, que está presente no algodão e outros tecidos, papel, etc., a ligação do conjugado à celulose coloca a entidade ligada em proximidade máxima com a superfície de ou que contém celulose. A invenção dessa maneira possibilita a marcação de entidades ligadas à tais superfícies. A invenção também fornece um produto que incorpora o conjugado polissacarídeo da invenção. O produto é convenientemente um produto de lavanderia tais como um produto de lavagem de tecido, por exemplo, um produto detergente, ou um produto condicionador de tecido. Neste caso a entidade ligada pode ser uma enzima, uma partícula carregando a fragrância, etc. A invenção também fornece um processo de ligação de marcação de uma entidade à celulose através do uso do conjugado polissacarídeo da invenção.

column13: ''CONJUGADO DE POLISSACARìDEO, PRODUTO, E, PROCESSO DE LIGAçãO DE MARCAçãO DE UMA PARTìCULA TRANSPORTANDO PERFUME PARA CELULOSE". Um conjugado de polissacarídeo compreende um polissacarídeo fixado a uma partícula transportando perfume, o conjugado de polissacarídeo sendo capaz de ligar-se a celulose. Polissacarídeos preferidos incluem xiloglucano de semente de tamarindo, goma de alfarroba e guar modificado com enzima. Devido ao conjugado de polissacarídeo ligar-se a celulose, que está presente em algodão e outros tecidos, papel, etc., a ligação do conjugado a celulose leva a partícula carregando perfume a uma proximidade íntima com a superfície de ou contendo celulose. A invenção possibilita, assim, marcação de partículas carregando perfume nestas superfícies. A invenção provê também um produto incorporando o conjugado de polissacarídeo da invenção. O produto é convenientemente um produto de lavanderia com um produto de lavagem de tecido, por exemplo, um produto detergente, ou um produto de condicionamento de tecido. A invenção provê também um processo para ligação de marcação de uma partícula transportando perfume para celulose por uso do conjugado de polissacarídeo da invenção.

column12: POLYSACCHARIDE CONJUGATES CAPABLE OF BINDING TO CELLULOSE
column13: A polysaccharide conjugate comprises a polysaccharide attached to a particle carrying perfume, the polysaccharide conjugate being capable of binding to cellulose. Preferred polysaccharides include tamarind seed xyloglucan, locust bean gum and enzyme modified guar. Because the polysaccharide conjugate binds to cellulose, which is present in cotton and other fabrics, paper, etc., binding of the conjugate to cellolose brings the perfume-bearing particle into close proximity to a surface of or containing cellulose. The invention thus enables targeting of perfume-bearing particles to such surfaces. The invention also provides a product incorporating the polysaccharide conjugate of the invention. The product is conveniently a laundry product such as a fabric washing product, e.g. a detergent product, or a fabric conditioning product. The invention also provides a method of targeting binding of a particle carrying perfume to cellulose by use of the polysaccharide conjugate of the invention.

column12: Selüloza bağlanabilen polisakkarit konjugesi.
column13: Bir polisakkarit konjugesi, moleküler agirligi en azindan 5000 olan birlestirilmis bir yapiya sahip bir polisakkarit konjugesi, selüloza baglanabilir. Tercih edilen polisakkaritler, demirhindi çekirdegi ksilogklukani, keçi boynuzu çekirdegi zamki ve enzimle modifiye edilmis guardir. Birlestirilen yapi, uygun olarak bir protein, örnegin bir enzim, antikor veya antikor parçasi, veya muhtemelen kendisiyle birlestirilmis koku gibi yararli bir maddeye sahip bir taneciktir. Polisakkarit konjugesi, pamuk ve diger kumaslar, kagit vs.' de bulunan selüloza baglandigindan, konjugenin selüloza baglanmasi, birlestirilmis yapiyi, selüloz içeren yüzeyin yakinina getirir. Bulus, bu sekilde birlestirilen yapilarin, bu tür yüzeylere hedeflenmesini mümkün kilar. Bulus, ayrica polisakkarit konjugesini içeren bir ürün ve polisakkarit konjugesinin kullanilmasiyla bir yapinin selüloza hedeflenerek baglanmasi için bir yöntem saglar.

column12: POLYSACCHARIDE CONJUGATE CAPABLE OF BINDING CELLULOSE
column13: A polysaccharide conjugate comprises a polysaccharide with an attached entity having a molecular weight of at least 5000, the polysaccharide conjugate being capable of binding to cellulose. Preferred polysaccharides include tamarind seed xyloglucan, locust bean gum and enzyme modified guar. The attached entity is suitably a protein such as an enzyme, antibody or antibody fragment, or a particle possibly having a benefit agent such as a fragrance associated therewith. Because the polysaccharide conjugate binds to cellulose, which is present in cotton and other fabrics, paper, etc., binding of the conjugate to cellulose brings the attached entity into close proximity to a surface of or containing cellulose. The invention thus enables targeting of attached entities to such surfaces. The invention also provides a product incorporating the polysaccharide conjugate of the invention. The product is conveniently a laundry product such as a fabric washing product, e.g., a detergent product, or a fabric conditioning product. In this case the attached entity may be an enzyme, a particle bearing fragrance, etc. The invention also provides a method of targeting binding of an entity to cellulose by use of the polysaccharide conjugate of the invention.

column12: Low electromagnetic emissions and improved signal quality video drive architecture for laser printers
column13: An electrophotographic image forming apparatus transfers image information relating to an image to be formed on a medium, while maintaining desired low levels of electromagnetic emissions. The apparatus includes an image processor that generates low-frequency image information signals containing the image information. A low-frequency interface is connected to the image processor for transferring the low-frequency image information signals. A control circuit, connected to the low-frequency interface, receives the low-frequency image information signals generated by the image processor. The control circuit operates on the low-frequency image information signals to form a high-frequency image information signal therefrom, where the high-frequency image information signal contains the image information. The apparatus also includes a high-frequency interface connected to the printhead control circuit for transferring the high-frequency image information signal. An image formation device, connected to the high-frequency interface, forms an image on the medium. The image formation device forms the image based on the image information contained within the high-frequency image information signal.

column12: Self-tapping fastner and method for attaching weatherseals
column13: A self-tapping fastener or fastening peg secures a weatherseal to a mounting surface of an automotive vehicle. A pointed, conical nose pierces the weatherseal to form an opening. In the preferred embodiment, the fastening peg is rotated at a first velocity as it is axially advanced toward the weatherseal to create an opening. The fastening peg is further axially advanced and rotated at a second velocity to advance a first flange through the pierced opening, thereby securing the fastening peg to the weatherseal. The weatherseal is then secured to a vehicle mounting surface by advancing a locking assembly through a pre-formed opening in the mounting surface.

column12: Signal processing system
column13: A signal processing system comprises an analogue shift register of the charge coupled type (24) fed from a sampling device (22) and controlled by a clock arrangement (26) having three independent clocks (26A, 26B and 26C). Clock (26A) determines the sampling rate of sampling device (22) and the rate at which such samples are clocked into register (24). Clock 26C determines the rate at which stored samples are clocked out of the register (24). Clocks 26A and 26C operate in the MHz range. Clock 26B operates in the KHz range and dictates the sample storage interval and clocks the stored samples through a number of storage sites in register (24) during the storage interval to reduce the adverse effects of geometrical and other inhomogeneities of the individual register sites on the individual stored samples.

column12: System and Method for Controlling Multiple Light Sources of a Laser Scanning System in an Imaging Apparatus
column13: A scanning system for use in an imaging apparatus includes a first light source and a second light source for emitting light beams for generating an image. A driver circuitry has first and second outputs connected to the first and second light sources, respectively, for controlling the first and second light sources. A signal transmitter includes a first interface for communicating a clock signal to the driver circuitry and a second interface for communicating an image information signal to the driver circuitry. During a clock cycle of the clock signal, the driver circuitry captures a first bit information from the image information signal at a rising edge of the clock signal and a second bit information from the image information signal at a falling edge of the clock signal. Thereafter, the driver circuitry drives the first and second light sources based on the first and second bit information captured, respectively.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the manufacture of moisture-proof, heat-sealable sheet wrapping materials
column13: A film-forming composition comprises an interpolymer of vinylidene chloride/acrylonitrile/acidic ethylenic compound prepared from a mixture of more than 80 per cent vinylidene chloride, between 0.1 and 2.5 per cent of acidic compound and the remainder acrylonitrile, and a solid polymer or interpolymer of ethylene incorporated in an amount up to 3 per cent of the weight of solids as a slip agent. The acidic ethylenic compound may be citraconic acid or anhydride, itaconic acid or anhydride, a mixture of citraconic and itaconic anhydrides obtained by distillation of citric acid, mesaconic acid or acrylic acid. The ratio of vinylidene chloride to acrylonitrile may be as high as 96 : 4, the preferred being 90 : 10. The interpolymers may be prepared as described in Specification 674,728. The composition may be applied in solution to a base film (see Group VIII), or may be converted into self-supporting films by casting &c. to produce a moisture-proof, heat-sealable sheet wrapping material. Suitable solvents are methyl ethyl ketone or a mixture of equal parts of toluene and methyl ethyl ketone. Specified ethylene interpolymers are those with 1,3-dioxolane; carbon monoxide; vinyl acetate, formate, chloride and cyanide; vinylidene chloride; acrylic, methacrylic and itaconic acids and their esters; tetrafluoroethylene; and styrene. Specification 600,164 also is referred to.

column12: VERFAHREN ZUR HERSTELLUNG EINER PARFÜMKAPSELZUSAMMENSETZUNG
PRODUCTION OF MOISTURE-PROOF FILMS
Improvements in or relating to the production of aqueous dispersions of vinylidene chloride copolymers and of moistureproof sheet wrapping material produced therefrom
column13: Aqueous dispersions of vinylidene chloride copolymers are made by emulsifying a mixture of vinylidene chloride and another monomer or monomers in which not more than 80 parts are vinylidene chloride, in an aqueous medium containing a water-soluble or water-dispersible dispersing agent selected from alkali metal or ammonium salts of long straight-chain alkyl or alkylene sulphates or sulphonates, comprising between 18 and 28 carbon atoms in the alkyl or alkylene group, maintaining the emulsion at a polymerization temperature, either under visible reflux action or in an autoclave, and preferably in the presence of a polymerization catalyst, until polymerization is substantially complete, then adding another dispersing agent selected from alkali metal or ammonium salts of an alkyl aryl sulphonate comprising between 4 and 12 carbon atoms in the alkyl group, or a water-soluble or water - dispersible condensation product of formaldehyde with a naphthalene sulphonic acid or alkali or ammonium salts thereof, or similar salts of straight-chain alkyl sulphates or sulphonates comprising between 8 and 12 carbon atoms in the alkyl group or alkyl sulphates or sulphonates comprising more than 12 carbon atoms in an alkyl group which comprises one or more branched chains. The comonomer may be acrylonitrile, vinyl chloride, methyl methacrylate, ethyl acrylate, alone or admixed with mesaconic acid, citraconic acid, or citraconic anhydride, or mixtures, or itaconic acid or anhydride or mixtures, or mixtures of citraconic and itaconic anhydrides obtainable from citric acid by distillation. The catalyst may be a mixture of ammonium persulphate and sodium metabisulphite. Specified dispersing agents are ammonium n-octadecyl sulphate, sodium n-octadecyl sulphate and/or sodium n-hexadecyl sulphate, sodium octadecenyl sulphate, sodium dodecyl benzene sulphonate, the condensation product of formaldehyde with sodium naphthalene beta-sulphonate, ammonium dodecyl sulphate, and ammonium 3,10-diethyl dodecyl sulphate. The dispersions may be used for coating organic, non-fibrous, hydrophilic films or sheets (see Group VIII) or made into self-supporting films by depositing the dispersed vinylidene chloride particles on to a base and stripping off the deposit, e.g. by the processes described in Specifications 669,907 and 680,709. Specification 663,645, [Group VIII], also is referred to.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR TESTING ENCAPSULATED CIRCUITS
column13: A method and apparatus (Fig. 3) for evaluating the suitability of an encapsulated electrical circuit (14) for use in a particular service environment provides for immersing the encapsulated circuit in a slightly conductive evaluating fluid (17) whose chemical composition approximates the environment into which the circuit will be placed in service. The thus-immersed circuit is then subjected to a reduced-pressure testing environment to draw air and other retained gases out of internal voids within the encapsulated circuit. The pressure of the testing environment is slowly increased to cause the encapsulated circuit to ingest a quantity of the evaluating fluid. An input signal (30) is then applied to the circuit and the circuit's response to the input signal is monitored (34) over a predetermined time period.

column12: VERFAHREN ZUR HERSTELLUNG VON N6-SUBSTITUIERTEN AMINOPURIN RIBOFURANOSE NUCLEOSIDEN
Circuit for supplying an amplitude modulated current to an R.F. stage of a radio transmitter.
column13: n pulse width modulation circuits for supplying amplitude modulated current to the anode of the R.F. stage of a high power radio transmitter, problems arise from carrier compression and from the need to protect the voltage source against excessive currents in the event of one or both of the switching valves breaking down. The protection circuit needs to handle an extremely large power: namely all the power supplied to the anode. The invention overcomes this problem by using two voltage sources (1, 9) one (1) of which provides carrier power whilst the other (9) drives a pulse width modulation amplifier (8) which modulates the carrier. Varying demand for power to the amplifier (8) thus does not effect the carrier. Therefore carrier compression is reduced. Also, only that voltage source (9) which feeds the amplifier needs a sophisticated fast acting protection system (11, 12) and since this does not supply all of the power to the anode the protection system is able to operate reliably.

column12: PATIENT INTERFACE ASSEMBLY DISCONNECT DETECTION
column13: A flow of breathable gas is delivered to a subject through a patient interface assembly. An enhanced technique for determining whether the airway of subject is disengaged from the patient interface assembly. A model that provides predicted values of a dynamic property of the flow of breathable gas is fit to measured values of the dynamic property. The model and/or the fit of the predicted values to the measured values are then analyzed to determine whether or not the airway of the subject is disengaged from the patient interface assembly. This provide enhanced determination of these conditions even in implementations in which a restrictive patient interface assembly is used.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the production of moisture-proof films
column13: In the production of moisture-proof films, regenerated cellulose, gelatin, &c. is treated with an aqueous dispersion, of pH 5-8, of a partially condensed urea or thiourea/formaldehyde or formaldehyde-aliphatic alcohol resin, the film is dried without curing the resin, and an aqueous dispersion, of pH 1-4, of a vinylidene polymer or copolymer is applied. The dispersion of the urea/formaldehyde resin, in which the mol. ratio of urea to formaldehyde may be 1 : 2-3, may contain a softening agent for the regenerated cellulose, e.g. glycerine. Examples disclose the production of dispersions (1) by refluxing at 98 DEG C. a mixture of urea or thiourea, formaldehyde, sodium acetate and cetyl trimethyl ammonium bromide, adding acetic acid to pH 5, cooling, and neutralizing to pH7 by caustic soda solution, and (2) by proceding as at (1) above with the addition of ethanol to the reaction mixture. Vinylidene chloride may be copolymerized with one or more of the following: acrylonitrile, vinyl chloride or acetate, styrene, ethyl acrylate, methyl or n-butyl methacrylate. The production of dispersions of vinylidene chloride/acrylonitrile is described in Specification 655,732. Long-chain alkyl sulphates may also be used as dispersing agents. After formation, the dispersion is acidified to pH 1-4 by citric, acetic, hydrochloric, &c. acid, or sulphur dioxide, or by ageing the dispersion under conditions which favour hydrolytic evolution of hydrochloric acid. Examples describe the preparation of dispersions (1) by copolymerizing at 45 DEG C. an emulsion of vinylidene chloride, acrylonitrile, ammonium octadecyl sulphate, ammonium persulphate and sodium metabisulphite, cooling, ageing, and acidifying with citric acid to pH 2.5; (2) by copolymerizing at 38 DEG C. a mixture of vinylidene chloride, methyl methacrylate, a condensation product of formaldehyde with naphthalene sulphonic acid (as dispersing agent), ammonium persulphate, and sodium metabisulphite, cooling and acidifying to pH 3 with hydrochloric acid.

column12: Fixture mount sensor with remote energy usage reporting
column13: An apparatus, and lighting systems and methods are provided for controlling and reporting power usage of an LED driver having an LED load driven by the LED driver. The apparatus is coupled to at least an auxiliary port of the LED driver for monitoring a dimming control voltage associated with the LED driver. The apparatus is configured to estimate the power usage of the LED driver and the LED load based on programmed relationships between the monitored dimming control voltage and a selected dimming profile associated with the LED driver. The dimming profile may either be a selected generic dimming profile for adequate reporting of the power usage or a selected specific dimming profile for increased accuracy of the power usage estimation. The apparatus is further configured to transmit the estimated power usage to an external device for dashboarding and energy savings purposes.

column12: A pulse width modulation system.
column13: A first source (1) of voltage V supplies sufficient rectified power for the carrier to the R.F. stage (7) of a radio transmitter. A second source (9) which exceeds twice the voltage V, powers a pulse width modulation amplifier (8) serving to amplify an incoming audio signal (A). The amplified signal (A) is applied, via a capacitor (16), to the load, thereby modulating the voltage V. Because the voltage of the second power source more than exceeds twice the voltage V, the amplifier can be operated at less than 100% pulse width modulation whilst still obtaining an amplification sufficient to achieve 100% modulation of the voltage V applied to the load.

column12: INSPIRATORY PRESSURE CONTROL IN VOLUME MODE VENTILATION
column13: The present disclosure pertains to a mechanical ventilator system configured to deliver a pressurized flow of breathable gas to the airway of a subject. The system is configured to generate the pressurized flow of breathable gas according to a volume control mode therapy regime that delivers a target tidal volume to the subject during inhalation. During an individual inhalation, the system is configured to determine and/or adjust an inspiratory pressure level of the pressurized flow of breathable gas of the volume control mode therapy regime. The inspiratory pressure level is adjusted such that during the inhalation the inspiratory pressure level is not reduced to impede respiratory effort by the subject responsive to the target tidal volume being exceeded during the inhalation. The system comprises one or more of a pressure generator, a subject interface, one or more sensors, one or more processors, a user interface, electronic storage, and/or other components.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the production of interpolymers and of moistureproof sheet wrapping material coated therewith
column13: Copolymers suitable for forming moisture-proof coating compositions are prepared by polymerizing a mixture comprising vinylidene chloride, acrylonitrile and one or more of the group consisting of citraconic acid anhydride and mesaconic acid. The acidic constituent may also be a mixture of citraconic and itaconic anhydrides obtained by distillation of citric acid. The preferred mixtures contain more than 80 per cent of vinylidene chloride (e.g. 87 per cent), between 0.5 and 10 per cent of the acidic ingredient and the remainder acrylonitrile. To produce a polymer sufficiently soluble in volatile organic solvents it is generally necessary to use a modifying compound of the formula R.R1C=O, where R and R1 may be hydrogen or a hydrocarbon radical, such as aldehydes and ketones, e.g. methyl isobutyl ketone. 6.5 per cent of modifying compound based on the weight of the polymerizable mixture is preferably used. Polymerization may be effected in bulk, solution or emulsion or by granular processes. A catalyst, e.g. ammonium persulphate, is preferably employed and may be used with an activator, e.g. sodium metabisulphite. Dispersing agents such as sodium long chain alkyl aryl sulphonates are used in emulsion polymerization and modifiers such as long chain mercaptans are preferably employed. An emulsion polymerization is described in which the mixture is maintained at 40 DEG C. with stirring for 20 hours and the product coagulated with aluminium sulphate. The polymers may be dissolved in such solvents as methyl ethyl ketone for application to cellulosic base films in the production of moisture-proof, heat-sealable sheet wrapping material. Specification 622,481 and U.S.A. Specification 2,278,415 are referred to.

column13: A self-tapping fastener (10) secures a weatherseal to a mounting surface of an automotive vehicle. A pointed, conical nose (12) pierces the weatherseal to form an opening. The fastener is rotated at a first velocity as it is axially advanced towards the weatherseal to create an opening. The fastener is further axially advanced and rotated at a second velocity to advance a first flange (16) through the pierced opening, thereby securing the fastening peg to the weatherseal. The weatherseal is then secured to a vehicle mounting surface by advancing a locking assembly (36) through a pre-formed opening in the mounting surface.

column12: An amplifier for pulse width modulated signals.
column13: In a pulse width modulated signal amplifier employing a tetrode valve S 1 , current to the grid G 1  and screen G 2  is controlled by constant current sources 19 and 24 respectively. Each constant current source comprises a switch S 3  a current sensor R 1 , R 2  and an inductor L 1 , L 2 . Each switch S 3  S 4  is switched on and off at a set frequency which, in the illustrated system, is the same as the pulse repetition frequency of the signal to be amplified. Each time the switch S 3  or S 4  is closed the current in the associated inductor L,, L 2  builds up until a set limit, determined by sensor R 1 , R 2  is reached whereupon the sensor opens the switch S 3 , S 4 . Thus, the period for which switches S 3  and S 4  remain closed varies to maintain the currents to G, and G 2  at the desired levels. By employing this technique the inductors L, and L 2  do not need to be as large as would be required using a known technique described in UK Patent Specification 1566095. Stray capacitances and resulting distortion are thus minimised. Also, since the switching frequencies of the switches S 3  and S 4  are identical the generation of harmonics of these frequencies, resulting in further interference with the signal to be amplified, is also avoided.

During an individual inhalation, the system is configured to determine and/or adjust an inspiratory pressure level of the pressurized flow of breathable gas of the volume control mode therapy regime. The inspiratory pressure level is adjusted such that during the inhalation the inspiratory pressure level is not reduced to impede respiratory effort by the subject responsive to the target tidal volume being exceeded during the inhalation. column12: A PULSE WIDTH MODULATOR
Method for automatically locating and commissioning lighting system components
column13: A control system for a vehicle parking area includes occupancy sensing devices, which may be associated with light fixtures. During a device commissioning mode, each device emits position signals and identifies signal characteristics of position signals received from proximate devices thereto. A central controller collects the position signals from the devices and generates a data set comprising identified locations for each device relative to predetermined baseline locations, based on the received position signals and the identified signal characteristics. The controller further maps the identified locations for each of the devices to specified locations in the parking area comprising the predetermined baseline locations. During a normal operating mode, the controller may generate signals directing drivers in the parking area to unoccupied parking spaces, and/or regulate a lighting state for light fixtures in the parking area based at least partly on detected occupancy states.

column13: A self-tapping fastener or fastening peg secures a weatherseal to a mounting surface of an automotive vehicle. A pointed, conical nose pierces the weatherseal to form an opening. column13: A lighting control system for a light fixture has an ambient light sensor mounted therein. A switching circuit provides power for driving lighting sources. A controller receives signals from the light sensor and regulates switching frequencies based on desired lighting output level and the ambient light condition. An ambient lighting channel extends from the ambient light sensor to an aperture between outer and inner surfaces of the housing. The ambient lighting channel may include a fiber optic light pipe which extends from the aperture to surround the light sensor. The fiber optic light pipe may extend through the aperture from the ambient light sensor to an ambient light source external to the light fixture. The light sensor may mount on a shared PCB with respect to the lighting sources, such as an LED array, and transmit ambient lighting information to the controller via a feedback loop.

column12: PATIENT INTERFACE ASSEMBLY DISCONNECT DETECTION
column13: A flow of breathable gas is delivered to a subject through a patient interface assembly. An enhanced technique for determining whether the airway of subject is disengaged from the patient interface assembly. A model that provides predicted values of a dynamic property of the flow of breathable gas is fit to measured values of the dynamic property. The model and/or the fit of the predicted values to the measured values are then analyzed to determine whether or not the airway of the subject is disengaged from the patient interface assembly. This provide enhanced determination of these conditions even in implementations in which a restrictive patient interface assembly is used.

column12: Improvements in focussing devices for cathode ray tubes
column13: 731,189. Cathode-ray tubes. GOODMANS INDUSTRIES, Ltd. Dec. 18, 1953 [Dec. 19, 1952], No. 32310/52. Class 39 (1). A focusing device for a C.R.T. comprises a supporting member 1, a first annular magnet 4 fixedly held in spaced relation to said member, a second annular magnet 5 disposed coaxially of the first magnet 4 and guided for axial movement relative thereto, and manually rotatable cam means 7 disposed between the magnet 5 and the supporting member 1 and operable to adjust the movable magnet 5 relatively to the fixed magnet 4. The supporting member 1 consists of an aluminium or other non-ferrous apertured plate adapted to encircle the stem of a C.R.T. and provided around its periphery with three parallel rods 2 to which is secured an aluminium or other non-ferrous carrier plate 3 carrying the fixed magnet 4, the movable magnet 5 being mounted on a second carrier plate 6 supported by apertured ears for sliding movement upon the rods 2. The cam means 7 consists of an apertured flanged disc rotatably supported upon a series of lugs bent up from the supporting plate 1, the flange portion of the disc being shaped to form a series of curved ramplike lobes 8 bearing against the ears on the carrier plate 6. The cam disc 7 is rotated by an arm 10, a curved blade spring 11 secured to the arm and bearing at its free end against the rear face of the supporting plate 1 providing a frictional lock. The magnetic repulsion of the two magnets 4 and 5 is assisted by coiled compression springs 9 encircling the rods 2 and bearing at their ends against the carrier plates 3 and 6. Means for centring the focusing device accurately upon a C.R.T. consists of a ring 12 adapted to fit closely upon the stem of the C.R.T. and formed with a slotted extension 13 riding on one of the rods 2 so that it can slide and pivot thereon, a handle 14 extending from the opposite side of the ring for displacing the focusing device. The Provisional Specification states that the cam disc may be rotatably supported on a cylindrical bearing surface fixed to the movable carrier plate or formed integral therewith by a pressing operation and provided with a plurality of arcuate cam elements which extend axially through complementary slots in the supporting plate. The cam elements may consist of appropriately bent metal strips fixed to the cam-plate or bent up therefrom. The cam may take the form of a drum or cup-like member, the rim or peripheral portion being shaped to define the cam elements whilst the body portion is apertured for location upon lugs provided on the inside or outside of the movable carrier plate. In another arrangement the cam is reversed, being mounted for rotation on the supporting member with the cam elements actuating the movable carrier plate either directly or through an interposed abutment member.

column12: Solar Thermal Tile
column13: A solar thermal tile 1 has a transparent portion 2 and a chassis 6. The transparent portion permits sunlight to heat a space below the solar tile, and the chassis has at least one protrusion 16,18, that overlaps an adjacent tile when both tiles are mounted. The chassis may include a non-transparent material, which may be a metal such as a folded sheet metal, or a plastic such as a moulded plastics material. The transparent portion may have peripheral edges, and may be formed from a polycarbonate sheet material. The solar thermal tile may be incorporated in a set of tiles on a building surface (70 fig 8) such as a roof or wall. The tile set further includes a photovoltaic cell within an externally identical chassis. The chassis of the photovoltaic tile (90 fig 8) may also include an airflow hole. The solar tile set may have a dimension that is a multiple of the other tiles in the tile set (2 fig 8). The space below the solar tile may include a heating space (35 fig 4) that includes a heating surface (36 fig 4) treated for maximising solar absorption. The heating surface may be in conductive communication with a pipe (37 fig 4) through which water flows. The heated water may be used to add heat to a domestic hot water system.

column12: SIMULATED BREATHING APPARATUS
column13: An apparatus ( 100 ) that simulates breathing, which is suitable for use when testing inhalers ( 14 ), comprises an inlet ( 22 ) to which, in use, an inhaler ( 14 ) can be connected, and a vacuum pumping system, which has a vacuum pump ( 106 ), a high-speed valve ( 102 ) and a flow sensing means ( 137, 112, 104, 114 ) interposed between the inlet ( 22 ) and the vacuum pump ( 106 ), and a controller ( 126 ). A user interface ( 134 ) enables a user to input a target flow profile ( 148, 150 ), which may correspond to human inspiration, such that, in operation, the controller ( 126 ) can control the operation of the vacuum pump ( 106 ) and the high-speed valve ( 102 ) so that the pressure and/or flow rate within the apparatus ( 100 ) matches the pressure ( 150 ) and/or flow rate ( 148 ) of the target flow profile in real-time or near-time.

column12: System and method for controlling multiple light sources of a laser scanning system in an imaging apparatus
column13: A scanning system for use in an imaging apparatus includes a first light source and a second light source for emitting light beams for generating an image. A driver circuitry has first and second outputs connected to the first and second light sources, respectively, for controlling the first and second light sources. A signal transmitter includes a first interface for communicating a clock signal to the driver circuitry and a second interface for communicating an image information signal to the driver circuitry. During a clock cycle of the clock signal, the driver circuitry captures a first bit information from the image information signal at a rising edge of the clock signal and a second bit information from the image information signal at a falling edge of the clock signal. Thereafter, the driver circuitry drives the first and second light sources based on the first and second bit information captured, respectively.

column12: Method and apparatus for testing encapsulated circuits
column13: A method and apparatus for evaluating the suitability of an encapsulated electrical circuit for use in a particular service environment provides for immersing the encapsulated circuit in a slightly conductive evaluating fluid whose chemical composition approximates the environment into which the circuit will be placed in service. The thus-immersed circuit is then subjected to a reduced-pressure testing environment to draw air and other retained gases out of internal voids within the encapsulated circuit. The pressure of the testing environment is slowly increased to cause the encapsulated circuit to ingest a quantity of the evaluating fluid. An input signal is then applied to the circuit and the circuit's response to the input signal is monitored over a predetermined time period.

column12: Improvements in Brake Motions of Looms for Weaving.
column13: 19,672. Singleton, T., Singleton, G. W., and Thornley, J. B. Sept. 29. Brakes.-The knocking-off lever 6, Figs. 1 and 2, of a loom is provided with a slot in which fits a pin 4 on a bell-crank 3 pivoted to a bracket 1. The actuation of the lever 6 thus rocks the bell-crank 3, and a pin 7 thereon depresses a pendent rod or tumbler lever 8 pivoted to the brake lever 12, which has a pin 15 for supporting a brake shoe 13 faced with leather &c. and pivoted on the same stud 14 as the lever 12. The brake is thus applied and positively retained against the action of the spring 19, the latter normally holding it out of action against a stop 17.
